1
00:00:22,625 --> 00:00:27,290
<i>[ Wind Chimes Jingling ]</i>

2
00:00:35,070 --> 00:00:37,500
<i>[ Man Speaking Arabic ]</i>

3
00:00:46,880 --> 00:00:50,110
<i>[ Men Conversing In Arabic ]</i>

4
00:00:53,690 --> 00:00:58,000
<i>[ Woman Singing In Hungarian ]</i>

5
00:02:34,860 --> 00:02:37,290
<i>[ Hungarian Song Ends ]</i>

6
00:03:08,660 --> 00:03:11,590
<i>[ Woman Vocalizing ]</i>

7
00:03:41,760 --> 00:03:45,320
[ Shouting In German ]

8
00:03:45,395 --> 00:03:48,420
[ Shouting ]

9
00:03:56,700 --> 00:04:00,470
[ Engine Sputtering ]

10
00:04:15,420 --> 00:04:18,860
<i>[ Train Whistle Blows ]</i>

11
00:04:30,640 --> 00:04:32,870
- How are you?
- Okay.

12
00:04:32,940 --> 00:04:35,100
Your leg
will be fine.

13
00:04:35,145 --> 00:04:37,800
A lot of shrapnel came out.
I saved you the pieces.

14
00:04:37,880 --> 00:04:41,000
You are the prettiest girl
I've ever seen.

15
00:04:41,080 --> 00:04:42,840
I don't think so.
Here.

16
00:04:42,920 --> 00:04:46,510
- Would you kiss me?
- No. I'll get you some tea.

17
00:04:46,590 --> 00:04:50,490
- It would mean such a lot to me.
- Would it?

18
00:04:55,350 --> 00:04:58,100
Thank you.

19
00:05:01,135 --> 00:05:04,160
- I can't sleep.
- Would you kiss me?

20
00:05:04,240 --> 00:05:07,100
- You're so pretty.
- Will you tuck me in, please?

21
00:05:07,100 --> 00:05:09,900
[ Laughing ] Very funny.
Go to sleep now.

22
00:05:09,979 --> 00:05:12,948
- Where's the doctor?
- Don't ask.

23
00:05:15,784 --> 00:05:19,550
[ Conversing In Arabic ]

24
00:05:22,558 --> 00:05:25,857
[ Conversation Continues ]

25
00:05:26,895 --> 00:05:30,991
[ Gasping, Groaning ]

26
00:05:41,176 --> 00:05:44,612
[ Breathing Heavily ]

27
00:05:50,919 --> 00:05:53,080
[ Camel Grunts ]

28
00:05:57,826 --> 00:06:01,523
[ Man Breathing Heavily ]

29
00:06:04,867 --> 00:06:06,994
[ Fly Buzzing ]

30
00:06:07,069 --> 00:06:10,197
[ Gasping, Gagging ]

31
00:06:19,848 --> 00:06:22,942
[ Chattering ]

32
00:06:24,920 --> 00:06:28,287
<i>[ Indistinct Conversations ]</i>

33
00:06:34,196 --> 00:06:37,654
God, I hate giving blood.
Can't stand needles.

34
00:06:44,173 --> 00:06:47,108
Is there anybody
from Picton?

35
00:06:47,176 --> 00:06:50,202
Picton?
I don't know.

36
00:06:50,279 --> 00:06:54,306
I'd like to see somebody
from home before I go.

37
00:07:01,957 --> 00:07:04,892
- Do we have anybody from Picton?
- Why Picton?

38
00:07:04,960 --> 00:07:07,758
He's from there. Edge of Lake Ontario,
right, soldier?

39
00:07:07,830 --> 00:07:11,357
<i>That's where your sweetie's from,</i>
<i>isn't it? Around there?</i>

40
00:07:11,433 --> 00:07:14,129
Ask him what company
he's with.

41
00:07:14,203 --> 00:07:18,401
- Third Canadian Fusiliers.
- Third Canadian Fusiliers.

42
00:07:21,276 --> 00:07:23,574
Does he know
Captain McGan?

43
00:07:23,645 --> 00:07:28,105
He bought it yesterday.
Shot to bits.

44
00:07:28,183 --> 00:07:30,743
- What did he say?
- Doesn't know him.

45
00:07:30,819 --> 00:07:34,118
<i>[ Shell Whistles, Explodes ]</i>

46
00:07:34,189 --> 00:07:37,090
<i>Hana, get down!</i>

47
00:07:37,159 --> 00:07:39,821
<i>[ Screaming, Shouting ]</i>

48
00:07:39,895 --> 00:07:43,023
[ Sobbing ]
He's dead. He's dead.

49
00:07:43,098 --> 00:07:45,032
[ Shouting ]

50
00:07:45,100 --> 00:07:48,228
[ Sobbing ]
He's dead.

51
00:07:48,303 --> 00:07:50,271
He's dead.

52
00:07:50,339 --> 00:07:53,433
<i>[ Explosions ]</i>

53
00:07:56,545 --> 00:07:59,810
[ Bottles Clinking ]

54
00:08:05,821 --> 00:08:09,348
[ Conversing In Arabic ]

55
00:08:20,135 --> 00:08:22,296
[ Arabic ]

56
00:08:27,276 --> 00:08:29,608
[ Breathing Heavily ]

57
00:08:29,678 --> 00:08:32,511
[ Chanting ]

58
00:08:32,581 --> 00:08:35,379
[ Continues ]

59
00:08:37,319 --> 00:08:40,686
<i>[ Chanting Continues,</i>
<i>Drumbeat ]</i>

60
00:08:40,756 --> 00:08:42,986
[ Arabic ]

61
00:08:43,058 --> 00:08:46,585
[ Chanting Continues ]

62
00:08:46,662 --> 00:08:49,096
[ Breathing Heavily ]

63
00:09:07,216 --> 00:09:10,811
[ Chattering ]

64
00:09:13,922 --> 00:09:17,619
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>Name, rank, serial number?</i>

65
00:09:17,693 --> 00:09:19,718
<i>[ Man #2 ]</i>
<i>No, sorry.</i>

66
00:09:19,795 --> 00:09:22,457
I think I was a pilot.

67
00:09:22,531 --> 00:09:26,126
I was found in the wreckage of a plane
at the beginning of the war.

68
00:09:26,201 --> 00:09:28,135
Can you remember
where you were born?

69
00:09:28,203 --> 00:09:30,865
Am I being interrogated?

70
00:09:30,939 --> 00:09:34,739
You should be trying to
trick me, make me speak German.

71
00:09:34,810 --> 00:09:37,142
- Which I can, by the way.
- Why?

72
00:09:37,212 --> 00:09:39,942
-<i>Are you German?</i>
- No.

73
00:09:40,015 --> 00:09:43,883
<i>How do you know you're not German</i>
<i>if you don't remember anything?</i>

74
00:09:43,952 --> 00:09:46,648
Might-- Might I have
a sip of water?

75
00:09:51,526 --> 00:09:54,051
<i>[ Sea Gulls Calling ]</i>

76
00:09:54,129 --> 00:09:56,324
[ Gulps ]

77
00:09:58,700 --> 00:10:00,793
- Thank you.
- It's okay.

78
00:10:02,571 --> 00:10:05,005
I remember
lots of things.

79
00:10:05,073 --> 00:10:09,567
I remember her garden,
plunging down to the sea.

80
00:10:09,645 --> 00:10:13,012
- <i>Nothing between you and France.</i>
- This was your garden?

81
00:10:13,081 --> 00:10:16,016
- Or my wife's.
- <i>You were married then?</i>

82
00:10:16,084 --> 00:10:20,453
I think so. Although I believe that
to be true of a number of Germans.

83
00:10:22,658 --> 00:10:24,592
<i>Look.</i>

84
00:10:24,660 --> 00:10:28,391
[ Gasping ]
I have this much lung.

85
00:10:28,463 --> 00:10:30,897
The rest of my organs
are packing up.

86
00:10:30,966 --> 00:10:34,333
What could it possibly matter
if I'm a Tutankhamen?

87
00:10:34,403 --> 00:10:38,362
I'm a bit of...
toast, my friend.

88
00:10:38,440 --> 00:10:42,001
Sorry I can't help you.

89
00:10:43,278 --> 00:10:46,406
[ Horn Honking ]

90
00:10:52,921 --> 00:10:56,288
<i>[ Breathing Heavily ]</i>

91
00:10:56,358 --> 00:10:58,553
Are you all right?

92
00:10:58,627 --> 00:11:01,653
I know you hate to be moved.
I'm sorry.

93
00:11:05,200 --> 00:11:08,363
- [ Honking ]
- Hana!

94
00:11:08,437 --> 00:11:11,838
-Jan?
- Hana!

95
00:11:11,907 --> 00:11:15,741
There's meant to be lace in the next
village. The boys are gonna take me.

96
00:11:15,811 --> 00:11:18,211
- You don't have any money, do ya?
- No.

97
00:11:18,280 --> 00:11:19,975
-Just in case there's a sale.
- <i>No.</i>

98
00:11:20,048 --> 00:11:21,675
Hana, I know you do.
Come on.

99
00:11:21,750 --> 00:11:23,308
- No!
- Oh, come on.

100
00:11:23,385 --> 00:11:25,910
I swear to God,
this'll be the last time. I swear.

101
00:11:25,988 --> 00:11:28,582
She's a softie.
She loves me.

102
00:11:30,892 --> 00:11:34,055
- I'll pay you back! I promise!
- [ Laughing ]

103
00:11:34,129 --> 00:11:36,996
I'm not sewing
anything else for you.

104
00:11:37,065 --> 00:11:39,260
I love you!

105
00:11:39,334 --> 00:11:42,565
Whoa!
Pienza, boys!

106
00:11:47,342 --> 00:11:49,310
[ Breathing Heavily ]

107
00:11:59,955 --> 00:12:01,889
<i>[ Man ] Get some water</i>
<i>over here!</i>

108
00:12:01,957 --> 00:12:06,087
Jan!
Oh, no!

109
00:12:07,496 --> 00:12:10,556
<i>Hana, where're</i>
<i>you going?</i>

110
00:12:10,632 --> 00:12:13,897
- Stay back!
- Stop, Hana!

111
00:12:15,003 --> 00:12:18,234
- Stay--
- [ Crying ]

112
00:12:21,676 --> 00:12:23,906
No!

113
00:12:23,979 --> 00:12:26,573
No!

114
00:13:10,992 --> 00:13:13,927
- Hey! Hey!
- Don't move!

115
00:13:13,995 --> 00:13:15,963
Don't move!
Don't move!

116
00:13:16,031 --> 00:13:18,261
Stand absolutely still!

117
00:13:18,333 --> 00:13:21,063
<i>You're walking in</i>
<i>a mine field!</i>

118
00:13:23,772 --> 00:13:26,240
Good.

119
00:13:26,308 --> 00:13:29,141
That's good.

120
00:13:29,211 --> 00:13:32,339
Just stay still
for me...

121
00:13:32,414 --> 00:13:34,678
and we'll be fine.

122
00:13:36,485 --> 00:13:38,749
What are you doing?

123
00:13:38,820 --> 00:13:41,983
What the bloody hell do
you think you're doing?

124
00:13:43,191 --> 00:13:46,126
<i>[ Hana ]</i>
<i>It's Jan's.</i>

125
00:13:47,329 --> 00:13:50,025
[ Sighs ]

126
00:14:13,388 --> 00:14:16,482
<i>[ Hana ] Are you in pain?</i>
<i>Do you need something?</i>

127
00:14:16,558 --> 00:14:18,492
- Yes.
- Okay.

128
00:14:20,262 --> 00:14:22,924
Are you okay?

129
00:14:22,998 --> 00:14:26,263
- You and Jan were--
- We keep moving him
in and out of the truck.

130
00:14:26,334 --> 00:14:29,428
Why? He's dying.
What's the point?

131
00:14:29,504 --> 00:14:32,098
We can hardly leave him.
Do you mean leave him?

132
00:14:32,174 --> 00:14:34,768
No, no,
I don't mean leave him.

133
00:14:43,084 --> 00:14:46,713
This will help you.

134
00:14:48,523 --> 00:14:51,014
I must be a curse.

135
00:14:51,092 --> 00:14:54,584
Anybody who loves me...
[ Sighs ]

136
00:14:55,730 --> 00:14:58,563
anybody who gets
close to me--

137
00:14:59,868 --> 00:15:02,098
Oh, I must be cursed.

138
00:15:07,442 --> 00:15:09,376
Which is it?

139
00:16:05,400 --> 00:16:07,834
[ Single Piano Key Plays ]

140
00:16:16,278 --> 00:16:18,269
[ Grunts ]

141
00:16:35,463 --> 00:16:39,456
- When he dies, I'll catch up.
- It's not safe here.

142
00:16:39,534 --> 00:16:43,300
The whole country's crawling with
bandits and Germans and God knows what.

143
00:16:43,371 --> 00:16:45,862
- It's madness! I can't allow it.
- The war is over.

144
00:16:45,940 --> 00:16:47,840
How can it be
desertion?

145
00:16:47,909 --> 00:16:51,242
It's not over everywhere.
I didn't mean literally.

146
00:16:51,313 --> 00:16:54,339
This is normal, a shock,
for all of us, Hana.

147
00:16:54,416 --> 00:16:57,817
I need morphine, a lot.
And a pistol.

148
00:17:02,624 --> 00:17:05,855
If anything ever happened to you,
I'd never forgive myself.

149
00:17:08,930 --> 00:17:11,694
We're heading
for Leghorn.

150
00:17:11,766 --> 00:17:14,064
''Livorno,''
the Italians call it.

151
00:17:14,135 --> 00:17:16,899
We'll expect you.

152
00:17:25,980 --> 00:17:27,914
Fine.

153
00:17:34,189 --> 00:17:36,623
- Thank you.
- You're welcome, ma'am.

154
00:17:39,894 --> 00:17:42,795
- Oh, Hana.
- I'll be okay.

155
00:17:42,864 --> 00:17:45,890
I'll catch up.
Good.

156
00:17:53,742 --> 00:17:56,438
<i>[ Sighs ]</i>

157
00:17:58,980 --> 00:18:01,881
<i>[ Muttering Song Lyrics ]</i>

158
00:18:01,950 --> 00:18:04,714
[ Continues ]

159
00:18:16,798 --> 00:18:20,199
[ Engines Droning ]

160
00:18:39,888 --> 00:18:41,981
[ Grunting ]

161
00:18:52,167 --> 00:18:55,068
What-- What was
all that banging?

162
00:18:55,136 --> 00:18:59,766
Are you-- Are you fighting rats
or the entire German army?

163
00:19:00,942 --> 00:19:05,242
No. I was repairing
the stairs.

164
00:19:05,313 --> 00:19:09,579
I found a library,
and the books were very useful.

165
00:19:09,651 --> 00:19:13,018
Before you find too many
uses for those books,

166
00:19:13,087 --> 00:19:15,555
you might
read some to me.

167
00:19:15,623 --> 00:19:18,217
I think they're all in Italian,
but I'll look, yes.

168
00:19:18,293 --> 00:19:20,955
- What about your own book?
- My book?

169
00:19:21,029 --> 00:19:24,123
Oh, yes,
the Herodotus.

170
00:19:24,199 --> 00:19:27,191
<i>Yes,you can read him.</i>

171
00:19:27,268 --> 00:19:30,260
Oh. I found plums.

172
00:19:30,338 --> 00:19:34,104
We have plums
in the orchard. There.

173
00:19:34,175 --> 00:19:36,973
We have an orchard.

174
00:19:37,045 --> 00:19:41,141
Herodotus is
the father of history.

175
00:19:41,216 --> 00:19:43,912
- Do you know that?
- I don't know anything.

176
00:19:54,262 --> 00:19:56,196
Hmm.

177
00:20:04,272 --> 00:20:06,536
<i>It's a</i>--

178
00:20:06,608 --> 00:20:09,873
It's a very plum...

179
00:20:09,944 --> 00:20:11,912
plum.

180
00:21:00,194 --> 00:21:01,718
<i>[ Thud ]</i>

181
00:21:03,364 --> 00:21:06,265
<i>[ Man Speaking Arabic ]</i>

182
00:21:06,334 --> 00:21:10,430
[ Responds In Arabic ]

183
00:21:32,460 --> 00:21:35,054
<i>[ Arabic ]</i>

184
00:21:36,564 --> 00:21:41,501
A mountain the shape
of a woman's back. Good, good.

185
00:22:05,593 --> 00:22:09,120
- Hello, Geoffrey!
- Madox, hello!

186
00:22:09,197 --> 00:22:12,633
- <i>Welcome to the expedition.</i>
- <i>How do you do? Geoffrey Clifton.</i>

187
00:22:12,700 --> 00:22:14,099
Splendid to finally
meet you all.

188
00:22:14,168 --> 00:22:16,102
This is Dante D'Agostino
and Diggy Bermann, our archaeologist.

189
00:22:16,170 --> 00:22:18,570
- Beautiful plane.
- This is Sharif Al Fouad, Egyptologist.

190
00:22:18,640 --> 00:22:21,632
- And this is my wife, Katharine.
- Hello.

191
00:22:21,709 --> 00:22:23,609
<i>We're your</i>
<i>new apprentices.</i>

192
00:22:23,678 --> 00:22:26,169
-<i>Welcome to the International Sand Club.</i>
-<i>[ Laughing ]</i>

193
00:22:26,247 --> 00:22:30,013
- To the International Sand Club.
- I'll get cups.

194
00:22:30,084 --> 00:22:32,518
- Marvelous plane. Did you look?
- Yes.

195
00:22:32,587 --> 00:22:35,647
Isn't it? A wedding present
from Katharine's parents.

196
00:22:35,723 --> 00:22:37,782
We're calling it
Rupert Bear.

197
00:22:37,859 --> 00:22:40,259
- Hello. Geoffrey Clifton.
- Almasy.

198
00:22:40,328 --> 00:22:43,729
We can finally consign my old bird
to the scrap heap.

199
00:22:43,798 --> 00:22:46,266
<i>Mrs. Clifton,</i>
<i>I'd like to present...</i>

200
00:22:46,334 --> 00:22:49,269
- Count Almasy.
- Hello.

201
00:22:49,337 --> 00:22:52,170
Geoffrey gave me your monograph
and I was reading up in the desert.

202
00:22:52,240 --> 00:22:54,868
- Very impressive.
- Thank you.

203
00:22:54,942 --> 00:22:58,343
I wanted to meet the man who could write
a long paper with so few adjectives.

204
00:22:58,413 --> 00:23:02,372
Well, a thing is still a thing,
no matter what you place in front of it.

205
00:23:02,450 --> 00:23:06,386
<i>Big car, slow car,</i>
<i>chauffeur-driven car.</i>

206
00:23:06,454 --> 00:23:09,389
-<i>[ Madox ] Broken car.</i>
- It's still a car.

207
00:23:09,457 --> 00:23:12,756
- Not much use, though.
-<i>[ Katharine ] Love?</i>

208
00:23:12,827 --> 00:23:16,490
Romantic love,
platonic love, filial love.

209
00:23:16,564 --> 00:23:19,032
- Quite different things, surely.
- <i>Uxoriousness.</i>

210
00:23:19,100 --> 00:23:23,594
That's my favorite kind of love.
Excessive love of one's wife.

211
00:23:23,671 --> 00:23:27,471
- Now there you have me.
- <i>[ Men Laughing ]</i>

212
00:23:27,542 --> 00:23:30,136
- They're tourists.
- Absolute rot.

213
00:23:30,211 --> 00:23:32,679
They're highly recommended
by the Royal Geographic Society.

214
00:23:32,747 --> 00:23:34,738
She's charming and
has read everything.

215
00:23:34,816 --> 00:23:37,649
- He's meant to be a ruddy good flier.
- We don't need another pilot.

216
00:23:37,719 --> 00:23:39,744
He can make aerial maps
of the whole route.

217
00:23:39,821 --> 00:23:42,483
<i>You can't explore</i>
<i>from the air, Madox.</i>

218
00:23:42,557 --> 00:23:45,549
<i>If you could explore from the air,</i>
<i>life would be very simple.</i>

219
00:23:46,561 --> 00:23:48,051
Contact.

220
00:23:50,131 --> 00:23:52,099
Contact.

221
00:25:08,810 --> 00:25:11,301
I should try
and move the bed.

222
00:25:11,379 --> 00:25:13,870
I want you to be able
to see the view.

223
00:25:13,948 --> 00:25:17,179
It's good. It's a view
from a monastery.

224
00:25:17,251 --> 00:25:20,709
- I can already see.
- How?

225
00:25:20,788 --> 00:25:23,518
- How can you see anything?
- No, no, not the window.

226
00:25:23,591 --> 00:25:26,287
I can't bear
the light anyway.

227
00:25:26,360 --> 00:25:28,851
I can see all the way
to the desert.

228
00:25:28,930 --> 00:25:30,830
I'm turning you.

229
00:25:30,898 --> 00:25:34,265
Exploring before the war,
making maps.

230
00:25:34,335 --> 00:25:37,566
Is there sand in my eyes?
Are you cleaning sand from my ears?

231
00:25:37,638 --> 00:25:41,165
No sand.
That's your morphine speaking.

232
00:25:48,416 --> 00:25:51,544
I can see my wife
in that view.

233
00:25:54,021 --> 00:25:57,013
Are you
remembering more?

234
00:25:57,091 --> 00:26:00,356
- Could I have a cigarette?
- Are you crazy?

235
00:26:01,662 --> 00:26:04,460
[ Coughing ]

236
00:26:04,532 --> 00:26:09,299
Why-- Why are you so determined
to keep me alive?

237
00:26:09,370 --> 00:26:12,828
[ Sighs ]
Because I'm a nurse.

238
00:26:38,733 --> 00:26:41,827
<i>[ Sound Of Hana's Feet Hopping ]</i>

239
00:26:41,903 --> 00:26:44,895
<i>[ Drumbeats, Chanting ]</i>

240
00:26:44,972 --> 00:26:47,532
[ Continues ]

241
00:26:53,981 --> 00:26:57,883
[ Foreign Language ]

242
00:27:01,722 --> 00:27:03,189
<i>Bravo.</i>

243
00:27:03,257 --> 00:27:05,851
We have an
old-fashioned tomato

244
00:27:05,927 --> 00:27:08,327
A Long Island potato

245
00:27:08,396 --> 00:27:11,524
<i>But yes</i>
<i>We have no bananas</i>

246
00:27:11,599 --> 00:27:13,863
<i>We have no bananas today</i>

247
00:27:13,935 --> 00:27:17,701
[ Arabic ]

248
00:27:17,772 --> 00:27:21,264
[ German ]

249
00:27:21,342 --> 00:27:23,276
[ Italian ]

250
00:27:23,344 --> 00:27:26,780
[ Arabic ]

251
00:27:26,847 --> 00:27:28,678
- <i>Next!</i>
- <i>Katharine!</i>

252
00:27:28,849 --> 00:27:31,784
[ Hana ] ''The King insisted that
he would find some way...

253
00:27:31,852 --> 00:27:33,843
''to prove beyond dispute...

254
00:27:33,921 --> 00:27:38,051
''that his wife
was fairest of all women.

255
00:27:38,125 --> 00:27:41,754
'''I will hide you in your room
where we sleep,' said Candaules--

256
00:27:41,829 --> 00:27:44,423
- said Candaules.''
- Candaules.

257
00:27:44,498 --> 00:27:47,126
''Candaules.''

258
00:27:47,201 --> 00:27:49,328
Candaules.

259
00:27:49,403 --> 00:27:53,396
Candaules tells Gyges that the Queen has
the same practice every night.

260
00:27:53,474 --> 00:27:56,443
She takes off
her clothes...

261
00:27:56,510 --> 00:28:00,446
and puts them on the chair
by the door to her room.

262
00:28:00,514 --> 00:28:02,982
<i>''And from where you stand,</i>

263
00:28:03,050 --> 00:28:06,577
<i>you will be able to gaze</i>
<i>on her at your leisure. '''</i>

264
00:28:08,022 --> 00:28:11,583
And that evening, it's exactly as
the King has told him.

265
00:28:11,659 --> 00:28:13,593
She goes
to the chair,

266
00:28:13,661 --> 00:28:15,788
removes her clothes
one by one,

267
00:28:15,863 --> 00:28:19,890
until she's standing naked
in full view of Gyges.

268
00:28:19,967 --> 00:28:24,631
And indeed, she was more lovely
than he could have imagined.

269
00:28:24,705 --> 00:28:28,300
But then,
the Queen looked up...

270
00:28:28,376 --> 00:28:32,506
and saw Gyges concealed
in the shadows.

271
00:28:32,580 --> 00:28:35,174
And although she said
nothing, she shuddered.

272
00:28:41,322 --> 00:28:43,552
And the next day,

273
00:28:43,624 --> 00:28:47,355
she sends for-- for Gyges
and challenged him.

274
00:28:47,428 --> 00:28:51,831
-<i>And hearing his story,</i>
<i>this is what she said.</i>
- Off with his head!

275
00:28:51,899 --> 00:28:53,764
[ Laughing ]

276
00:28:56,103 --> 00:28:59,129
She said, ''Either you
must submit to death...

277
00:28:59,206 --> 00:29:02,141
''for gazing on that
which you should not,

278
00:29:02,209 --> 00:29:04,734
''or else kill my husband
who has shamed me...

279
00:29:06,614 --> 00:29:09,708
<i>and become King</i>
<i>in his place. ''</i>

280
00:29:11,919 --> 00:29:14,547
So Gyges kills the King,

281
00:29:14,622 --> 00:29:18,752
marries the Queen and becomes ruler
of Lydia for 28 years.

282
00:29:20,728 --> 00:29:22,662
The end.

283
00:29:25,299 --> 00:29:28,029
Shall I spin
the bottle?

284
00:29:28,102 --> 00:29:30,696
[ Madox ] So, Geoffrey,
let that be a lesson to you.

285
00:29:30,771 --> 00:29:33,205
- [ Katharine ] D'Agostino!
- D'Agostino!

286
00:29:34,408 --> 00:29:36,842
<i>Are you asleep?</i>

287
00:29:37,912 --> 00:29:40,506
Yes.

288
00:29:40,581 --> 00:29:43,846
No. I'm dropping off.

289
00:30:24,425 --> 00:30:26,359
[ Cawing ]

290
00:30:26,427 --> 00:30:29,294
Go away!

291
00:30:29,363 --> 00:30:31,991
Go! Go!

292
00:30:41,909 --> 00:30:43,843
[ Grunts ]

293
00:30:46,714 --> 00:30:48,682
<i>Buon giorno.</i>

294
00:30:49,884 --> 00:30:52,853
- <i>Hana?</i>
- What do you want?

295
00:30:52,920 --> 00:30:55,855
I met your friend Mary.

296
00:30:55,923 --> 00:30:59,188
She said I should stop and see
if you were all right.

297
00:30:59,260 --> 00:31:04,061
<i>Apparently we're neighbors. My house</i>
<i>is two blocks from yours in Montreal.</i>

298
00:31:04,131 --> 00:31:06,827
<i>Cabot, north of Laurier.</i>

299
00:31:06,901 --> 00:31:09,768
- <i>Bonjour.</i>
- <i>Bonjour.</i>

300
00:31:12,072 --> 00:31:14,097
For you.

301
00:31:14,175 --> 00:31:16,370
<i>I'd like to take credit for it,</i>
<i>but it's from Mary.</i>

302
00:31:16,443 --> 00:31:20,038
My name is David Caravaggio,
but nobody ever called me David.

303
00:31:20,114 --> 00:31:24,710
Caravaggio they find
too absurd to miss out on.

304
00:31:24,785 --> 00:31:26,446
Oh!

305
00:31:26,520 --> 00:31:28,988
[ Snickers ]
Oh!

306
00:31:29,056 --> 00:31:31,286
Oh, shit.
Stupid hands.

307
00:31:31,358 --> 00:31:34,759
<i>Let me do that.</i>

308
00:31:40,501 --> 00:31:43,163
They're fresh.

309
00:31:43,237 --> 00:31:45,671
I haven't had
an egg in--

310
00:31:48,142 --> 00:31:50,667
Have you noticed
there are chickens?

311
00:31:50,744 --> 00:31:52,939
In Italy, you get chickens
but no eggs.

312
00:31:53,013 --> 00:31:55,811
In Africa, they're always eggs
but never chickens.

313
00:31:55,883 --> 00:31:59,319
- Who's separating them?
- You were in Africa?

314
00:31:59,386 --> 00:32:01,251
Yes, I was.

315
00:32:01,322 --> 00:32:04,291
So was my patient.

316
00:32:04,358 --> 00:32:07,350
Look, I'd like to
stay for a while.

317
00:32:07,428 --> 00:32:09,396
I have to do
some work here.

318
00:32:09,463 --> 00:32:12,830
<i>I speak the language.</i>
<i>There are partisans to be disarmed.</i>

319
00:32:12,900 --> 00:32:16,700
We embrace them and see
if we can relieve them of their weapons,

320
00:32:16,770 --> 00:32:18,829
you know,
while we hide.

321
00:32:18,906 --> 00:32:22,467
I was a thief, so the army
thought I'd be good at it.

322
00:32:22,543 --> 00:32:25,341
- So you can shoot a pistol?
- No.

323
00:32:25,412 --> 00:32:28,279
Do you have a problem
with those?

324
00:32:30,117 --> 00:32:31,584
No.

325
00:32:31,652 --> 00:32:34,280
- I should look at them before you go.
- <i>Look.</i>

326
00:32:34,355 --> 00:32:36,755
It's a big place.
We needn't disturb each other.

327
00:32:36,824 --> 00:32:39,088
<i>I'll sleep in the stable.</i>

328
00:32:39,159 --> 00:32:41,184
It doesn't matter where I sleep.
I don't sleep.

329
00:32:41,262 --> 00:32:44,356
I don't know what Mary told you
about me, but I don't need company.

330
00:32:44,431 --> 00:32:47,525
I don't need
to be looked after.

331
00:32:51,672 --> 00:32:54,903
There is a man
downstairs.

332
00:32:54,975 --> 00:32:58,376
He brought us eggs.
He might stay.

333
00:32:58,445 --> 00:33:01,312
Why?
Can he lay eggs?

334
00:33:01,382 --> 00:33:03,475
He's Canadian.

335
00:33:03,550 --> 00:33:07,577
Why are people always so happy when they
collide with one from the same place?

336
00:33:07,655 --> 00:33:10,556
What happened in Montreal
when you passed a man in the street?

337
00:33:10,624 --> 00:33:13,718
Did you invite him
to live with you?

338
00:33:15,129 --> 00:33:17,427
He needn't
disturb you.

339
00:33:17,498 --> 00:33:20,058
He can't.
I'm already disturbed.

340
00:33:20,134 --> 00:33:22,932
[ Sighs ]

341
00:33:23,003 --> 00:33:26,905
There's a war. Where you come from
becomes important.

342
00:33:26,974 --> 00:33:30,535
<i>[ Patient ]</i>
<i>Why? I hate that idea.</i>

343
00:33:35,683 --> 00:33:38,652
Ah!
It's gonna work.

344
00:33:39,720 --> 00:33:42,314
<i>Gently.</i>

345
00:33:42,389 --> 00:33:45,256
[ Knocking ]

346
00:33:46,393 --> 00:33:48,361
Can I help?

347
00:33:48,429 --> 00:33:50,329
It's finished.

348
00:33:50,397 --> 00:33:52,661
So, you're our
Canadian pickpocket?

349
00:33:52,733 --> 00:33:55,395
<i>Thief</i> I think
is more accurate.

350
00:33:55,469 --> 00:34:00,065
I understand you were in Africa.
Whereabouts?

351
00:34:00,140 --> 00:34:02,734
Oh, all over.

352
00:34:02,810 --> 00:34:06,075
All over?

353
00:34:06,146 --> 00:34:09,673
I kept trying to cover
a very modest portion and still failed.

354
00:34:09,750 --> 00:34:12,719
-<i>Are you leaving us?</i>
- Yes.

355
00:34:12,786 --> 00:34:15,346
Now's our opportunity
to swap war wounds.

356
00:34:15,422 --> 00:34:18,721
[ Laughs ]
Then I'm definitely going.

357
00:34:22,296 --> 00:34:25,129
Does she have
war wounds?

358
00:34:25,199 --> 00:34:27,429
I think anybody
she ever loves...

359
00:34:27,501 --> 00:34:29,799
<i>tends to die on her.</i>

360
00:34:29,870 --> 00:34:32,896
-<i>Are you planning to be the exception?</i>
- <i>Me?</i>

361
00:34:32,973 --> 00:34:35,271
<i>[ Laughs ]</i>
<i>I think you've got...</i>

362
00:34:35,342 --> 00:34:37,640
the wrong end
of the stick, old boy.

363
00:34:37,711 --> 00:34:40,475
<i>So...</i>

364
00:34:40,547 --> 00:34:42,481
<i>Caravaggio.</i>

365
00:34:42,549 --> 00:34:45,814
Hana thinks
you invented your name.

366
00:34:45,886 --> 00:34:48,480
And you've
forgotten yours.

367
00:34:48,555 --> 00:34:53,686
I said that no one would ever invent
such a preposterous name.

368
00:34:53,761 --> 00:34:56,093
And I said you can
forget everything,

369
00:34:57,664 --> 00:35:00,633
but you never forget
your name.

370
00:35:00,701 --> 00:35:03,067
Count Almasy.

371
00:35:03,137 --> 00:35:05,469
<i>That name mean</i>
<i>anything to you?</i>

372
00:35:05,539 --> 00:35:07,905
<i>Or Katharine Clifton?</i>

373
00:35:07,975 --> 00:35:10,910
[ People Chattering ]

374
00:35:16,517 --> 00:35:18,451
Oh, I'm sorry.

375
00:35:18,519 --> 00:35:21,682
- How much did you pay?
- Oh, hello.

376
00:35:21,755 --> 00:35:25,657
They don't see foreign women
in this market. How much did you pay?

377
00:35:25,726 --> 00:35:28,422
Um, ¢G7, ¢G8, I suppose.

378
00:35:28,495 --> 00:35:30,929
- Which store?
- Why?

379
00:35:30,998 --> 00:35:34,365
You've been cheated.
Oh, don't worry, we'll take it back.

380
00:35:34,435 --> 00:35:36,369
I don't want
to take it back.

381
00:35:36,437 --> 00:35:39,668
- This is not worth ¢G8.
- It is to me.

382
00:35:39,740 --> 00:35:42,231
- Did you bargain?
- I don't care to bargain.

383
00:35:42,309 --> 00:35:44,504
That insults them.

384
00:35:46,113 --> 00:35:49,810
I don't believe that. I think
that you're insulted by me somehow.

385
00:35:49,883 --> 00:35:53,250
I'd be very happy to obtain
the correct price for this.

386
00:35:53,320 --> 00:35:56,016
I apologize
if I appear abrupt.

387
00:35:56,089 --> 00:35:58,489
I'm rusty at social graces.

388
00:36:02,930 --> 00:36:04,955
How do you find Cairo?

389
00:36:05,032 --> 00:36:08,832
- Did you visit the pyramids?
- Excuse me.

390
00:36:08,902 --> 00:36:11,564
Or the Sphinx?

391
00:36:14,775 --> 00:36:19,109
<i>[ Almasy ] Latitude, 25, 33.</i>
<i>Longitude, 25, 1 6.</i>

392
00:36:19,179 --> 00:36:23,115
<i>We attempt to drive northeast of Kofer,</i>
<i>we'll leave our bones in the desert.</i>

393
00:36:23,183 --> 00:36:25,617
- I disagree.
- You're Hungarian. You always disagree.

394
00:36:25,686 --> 00:36:27,745
- Good evening, gentlemen.
- Good evening.

395
00:36:27,821 --> 00:36:29,914
- How is your charming wife?
- <i>Marvelous.</i>

396
00:36:29,990 --> 00:36:32,288
She's in love
with the hotel plumbing.

397
00:36:32,359 --> 00:36:34,486
<i>She's either in the swimming pool.</i>
<i>She swims for hours.</i>

398
00:36:34,561 --> 00:36:37,496
She's a fish. It's quite incredible.
Or she's in the bath.

399
00:36:37,564 --> 00:36:40,692
- [ Laughing ]
- Actually, she's just outside.

400
00:36:42,102 --> 00:36:44,332
Chaps only
in the Long Bar.

401
00:36:48,775 --> 00:36:50,743
Mrs. Clifton.

402
00:36:50,811 --> 00:36:55,271
<i>You'll have to forgive us. We're not</i>
<i>accustomed to the company of women.</i>

403
00:36:55,349 --> 00:36:59,046
Not at all. I was thoroughly
enjoying my book.

404
00:36:59,119 --> 00:37:01,986
- The team is in mourning, darling.
- Oh, really?

405
00:37:02,055 --> 00:37:05,388
I'm afraid we're not having much luck
obtaining funds for the expedition.

406
00:37:05,459 --> 00:37:07,393
Oh. Well, what'll you do?

407
00:37:07,461 --> 00:37:09,895
More modest expedition,
or even wait a year.

408
00:37:09,963 --> 00:37:12,955
- It's a disaster.
- Remind our families we still exist.

409
00:37:13,033 --> 00:37:15,024
Good heavens,
are you married, Madox?

410
00:37:15,102 --> 00:37:18,230
Very much so.
We all are.

411
00:37:18,305 --> 00:37:20,739
-<i>Save my friend Almasy here.</i>
- I feel much better.

412
00:37:20,807 --> 00:37:24,538
Don't you, darling?
We were feeling rather self-conscious.

413
00:37:24,611 --> 00:37:26,738
Let's toast, then.
Absent wives.

414
00:37:26,813 --> 00:37:29,543
- [ All ] Absent wives.
- And present ones.

415
00:37:29,616 --> 00:37:31,243
And future ones.

416
00:37:34,988 --> 00:37:37,889
<i>[Jazz ]</i>

417
00:37:49,570 --> 00:37:52,232
<i>[ Song Ends ]</i>

418
00:37:52,306 --> 00:37:54,240
Thank you.

419
00:37:54,308 --> 00:37:57,106
Excuse me.
May I?

420
00:37:57,177 --> 00:38:00,112
<i>[ Slow ]</i>

421
00:38:11,758 --> 00:38:15,159
- Why did you follow me yesterday?
- I'm sorry. What?

422
00:38:15,228 --> 00:38:17,822
After the market,
you followed me to the hotel.

423
00:38:17,898 --> 00:38:22,028
I was concerned. A woman
in that part of Cairo, a European woman.

424
00:38:22,102 --> 00:38:24,593
- I felt obliged to.
- You felt obliged to?

425
00:38:24,671 --> 00:38:27,538
As the wife of
one of our party.

426
00:38:27,608 --> 00:38:30,668
So why follow me?
Escort me, by all means.

427
00:38:30,744 --> 00:38:34,009
But following me
is predatory, isn't it?

428
00:39:13,420 --> 00:39:16,719
[ Snoring ]

429
00:39:16,790 --> 00:39:19,850
Could I ask you
to move?

430
00:39:20,927 --> 00:39:23,054
I'm sorry, but I--

431
00:39:24,865 --> 00:39:27,834
I'm sorry.
Of course.

432
00:39:27,901 --> 00:39:30,836
- <i>It's just when you move.</i>
- How stupid of me.

433
00:39:30,904 --> 00:39:35,534
- I can't really bear the pressure--
- Are you all right?

434
00:39:35,609 --> 00:39:37,941
I was dreaming.
Awful.

435
00:40:15,482 --> 00:40:18,383
[ Crying ]

436
00:40:25,058 --> 00:40:28,619
[ Sobbing ]

437
00:40:28,695 --> 00:40:30,629
Hana.

438
00:40:33,333 --> 00:40:36,928
Hana, are you
all right?

439
00:40:37,003 --> 00:40:39,597
Leave me alone.

440
00:40:40,941 --> 00:40:42,875
[ Sobs ]

441
00:41:00,660 --> 00:41:02,924
You're in love with him,
aren't you?

442
00:41:02,996 --> 00:41:06,056
<i>Your poor patient.</i>

443
00:41:06,133 --> 00:41:09,068
<i>You think he's a saint</i>
<i>because of the way he looks.</i>

444
00:41:09,136 --> 00:41:12,230
I don't think he is.

445
00:41:12,305 --> 00:41:14,603
I'm not so
in love with him.

446
00:41:14,674 --> 00:41:18,974
I'm in love with ghosts.

447
00:41:19,045 --> 00:41:22,139
So is he.
He's in love with ghosts.

448
00:41:22,215 --> 00:41:24,513
What if I told you
he did this to me?

449
00:41:27,687 --> 00:41:31,020
How could he have?
When?

450
00:41:31,091 --> 00:41:33,651
I'm one of his ghosts,
and he wouldn't even know it.

451
00:41:33,727 --> 00:41:37,629
- I don't know what that means.
-<i>Ask your saint who he is.</i>

452
00:41:38,632 --> 00:41:40,964
Ask him
who he's killed.

453
00:41:44,237 --> 00:41:48,674
[ Sobbing ] Please, don't creep
around this house.

454
00:41:48,742 --> 00:41:51,142
<i>See, I don't think</i>
<i>he's forgotten anything!</i>

455
00:41:51,211 --> 00:41:54,078
<i>I think he</i> wants <i>to forget!</i>

456
00:41:56,016 --> 00:41:58,314
<i>[ Clifton ]</i>
<i>Gentlemen, to mapmaking.</i>

457
00:41:58,385 --> 00:42:00,285
[ All ]
To mapmaking!

458
00:42:00,353 --> 00:42:02,719
And a special thank you
to Geoffrey and Katharine,

459
00:42:02,789 --> 00:42:06,987
without whose fund-raising heroics,
we'd still be kicking our heels.

460
00:42:07,060 --> 00:42:09,494
- To arm-twisting.
- [ All ] Arm-twisting.

461
00:42:09,563 --> 00:42:13,659
Did Katharine say Geoffrey
has to fly back to Cairo?

462
00:42:13,733 --> 00:42:16,497
Return the favor.
Take a few photographs for the army.

463
00:42:16,570 --> 00:42:18,970
Oh, um, what kind
of photographs?

464
00:42:19,039 --> 00:42:20,973
Portraits.

465
00:42:21,041 --> 00:42:23,509
The brigadier,
the brigadier's wife,

466
00:42:23,577 --> 00:42:27,604
the brigadier's dog, brigadier
by the pyramids, brigadier breathing.

467
00:42:27,681 --> 00:42:30,172
<i>And I shall,</i>
<i>of course, be bereft.</i>

468
00:42:30,250 --> 00:42:33,083
I'll finally be able to
explore the Cairo nightlife.

469
00:42:33,153 --> 00:42:36,088
I shall produce an authoritative guide
to the zinc bars and--

470
00:42:36,156 --> 00:42:38,886
I want to say <i>hareems.</i> Are we
in the right country for <i>hareems</i>?

471
00:42:38,959 --> 00:42:40,927
<i>[ Madox ]</i>
<i>Harems.</i>

472
00:42:46,032 --> 00:42:48,592
- Bye, my love.
- Travel safe.

473
00:42:48,668 --> 00:42:50,932
Catch up
in a week.

474
00:42:53,573 --> 00:42:56,906
Clifton, safe journey.

475
00:42:56,977 --> 00:43:01,243
You too. Good luck.
Glad the funds have turned up.

476
00:43:01,314 --> 00:43:04,283
Clifton.

477
00:43:07,387 --> 00:43:09,981
This is probably
none of my business.

478
00:43:10,056 --> 00:43:12,889
Your wife.

479
00:43:12,959 --> 00:43:16,258
- Think it's appropriate to leave her?
- Appropriate?

480
00:43:16,329 --> 00:43:20,095
Well, the desert is, it's, uh--
for a woman, it's very tough.

481
00:43:20,166 --> 00:43:22,430
I wonder if it's
not too much for her.

482
00:43:22,502 --> 00:43:24,993
Are you mad? Katharine loves it here.
She told me yesterday.

483
00:43:25,071 --> 00:43:28,097
- All the same, were I you--
- I've known Katharine
since she was three.

484
00:43:28,174 --> 00:43:30,870
We were practically brother and sister
before we were man and wife.

485
00:43:30,944 --> 00:43:33,378
I think I'd know what is and what isn't
too much for her.

486
00:43:33,446 --> 00:43:36,279
I think
she'd know herself.

487
00:43:36,349 --> 00:43:38,317
Very well.

488
00:43:38,385 --> 00:43:41,286
Why are you people
so threatened by a woman?

489
00:43:51,965 --> 00:43:54,559
<i>[ Piano ]</i>

490
00:44:19,159 --> 00:44:21,093
[ Tapping ]

491
00:44:23,930 --> 00:44:26,125
I have come to love...

492
00:44:26,199 --> 00:44:29,999
that little tap of the
fingernail against the syringe.

493
00:44:31,071 --> 00:44:33,801
Tap.

494
00:44:33,873 --> 00:44:36,740
Tap.

495
00:44:36,810 --> 00:44:38,744
Tap.

496
00:44:38,812 --> 00:44:42,509
<i>[ Continues ]</i>

497
00:44:59,466 --> 00:45:03,095
- [ Gunshot ]
- Stop playing! Please, stop playing.

498
00:45:07,774 --> 00:45:10,709
I don't have the key
to that door. You--

499
00:45:13,646 --> 00:45:16,911
The Germans were here.
The Germans were all over this area.

500
00:45:16,983 --> 00:45:19,451
They left mines
everywhere.

501
00:45:19,519 --> 00:45:22,010
And pianos were their
favorite hiding places.

502
00:45:22,088 --> 00:45:24,522
I see.
Sorry.

503
00:45:29,829 --> 00:45:33,595
Then maybe you're safe
as long as you only play Bach.

504
00:45:35,035 --> 00:45:37,265
He's German.

505
00:45:38,471 --> 00:45:41,167
Is something funny?

506
00:45:41,241 --> 00:45:43,641
No. I'm sorry.

507
00:45:58,258 --> 00:46:00,556
I've met you before.

508
00:46:00,627 --> 00:46:04,119
I don't think so.

509
00:46:14,374 --> 00:46:16,342
Look. See?

510
00:46:16,409 --> 00:46:19,435
Move that,
and no more Bach.

511
00:46:19,512 --> 00:46:22,948
Lieutenant!
Are you all right, sir?

512
00:46:23,016 --> 00:46:25,484
<i>Fine, Sergeant.</i>

513
00:46:25,552 --> 00:46:27,452
So you're working
with the Italians.

514
00:46:27,520 --> 00:46:29,613
Yeah, trying to get them
to give up their weapons.

515
00:46:29,689 --> 00:46:32,385
<i>I was a thief,so the army</i>
<i>thought I'd be good at it.</i>

516
00:46:32,459 --> 00:46:34,859
<i>I like the Italians.</i>

517
00:46:34,928 --> 00:46:37,226
<i>[ Hana ]</i>
<i>He wants us to move out.</i>

518
00:46:37,297 --> 00:46:40,789
He says there could be
50 more mines in the building.

519
00:46:40,867 --> 00:46:45,236
<i>[ Hana ] He thinks I'm mad</i>
<i>because I laugh at him.</i>

520
00:46:45,305 --> 00:46:48,297
He's Indian.

521
00:46:48,374 --> 00:46:52,208
- He wears a turban.
- No, he's Sikh.

522
00:46:52,278 --> 00:46:54,712
<i>Ifhe wears a turban,</i>
<i>he's Sikh.</i>

523
00:46:54,781 --> 00:46:56,806
I'll probably marry him.

524
00:46:56,883 --> 00:47:00,080
Really?
That's sudden.

525
00:47:00,153 --> 00:47:02,144
My mother
always told me...

526
00:47:02,222 --> 00:47:05,953
I would summon my husband
by playing the piano.

527
00:47:07,427 --> 00:47:10,362
[ Breathing Heavily ]

528
00:47:12,165 --> 00:47:16,101
- I liked it better when
there were just the two of us.
- Why? Is he staying?

529
00:47:16,169 --> 00:47:18,899
With his sergeant,
a Mr. Hardy.

530
00:47:20,273 --> 00:47:24,232
We should charge.
Doesn't anyone have a job to do?

531
00:47:24,310 --> 00:47:28,246
They have to clear all the roads
of mines. That's a big job.

532
00:47:28,314 --> 00:47:31,511
<i>In that case, I</i>--
<i>I suppose we can't charge.</i>

533
00:47:31,584 --> 00:47:34,075
No, we can't.

534
00:47:36,956 --> 00:47:39,424
Thank you.

535
00:47:43,129 --> 00:47:46,064
<i>[ Engines Drone ]</i>

536
00:48:05,785 --> 00:48:10,313
[ Muttering Song Lyrics ]

537
00:48:19,165 --> 00:48:21,599
Flat foot floogee
with the floy floy

538
00:48:21,668 --> 00:48:26,435
[ Humming ]

539
00:48:26,506 --> 00:48:29,202
Flat foot floogee
with the floy floy

540
00:48:29,275 --> 00:48:31,800
Flat foot floogee
with the floy floy

541
00:48:31,878 --> 00:48:36,247
I've been thinking. How does someone
like you decide to come to the desert?

542
00:48:36,316 --> 00:48:38,216
What is it? You--

543
00:48:38,284 --> 00:48:41,549
You're doing whatever you're doing in
your castle, or wherever it is you live,

544
00:48:41,621 --> 00:48:45,284
and one day you say,
''I have to get to the desert,'' or what?

545
00:48:45,358 --> 00:48:50,091
I once traveled with a guide
who was taking me to Faya.

546
00:48:50,163 --> 00:48:54,031
He didn't speak
for nine hours.

547
00:48:56,536 --> 00:49:01,235
<i>At the end of it, he pointed</i>
<i>at the horizon and said, ''Faya. ''</i>

548
00:49:01,307 --> 00:49:04,242
That was a good day.

549
00:49:14,887 --> 00:49:17,447
Actually, you sing.

550
00:49:19,292 --> 00:49:21,783
- What?
- You sing.

551
00:49:21,861 --> 00:49:24,329
All the time.

552
00:49:24,397 --> 00:49:26,524
- I do not.
- Ask Al Auf.

553
00:49:27,900 --> 00:49:29,868
Al Auf!.

554
00:49:31,604 --> 00:49:35,472
- [ Arabic ]
- [ Al Auf Laughs ]

555
00:49:35,541 --> 00:49:38,977
[ Arabic ]

556
00:49:39,045 --> 00:49:41,707
<i>[ Al Auf Singing ]</i>

557
00:49:41,781 --> 00:49:44,773
<i>[ Katharine ]</i>  <i>You'd better be ready</i>
<i>about half past 8:00</i>

558
00:49:44,851 --> 00:49:47,046
Remember, honey
Don't be late

559
00:49:47,120 --> 00:49:50,886
'Cause I'll be there
when the band starts playing

560
00:49:50,957 --> 00:49:52,982
Gonna dance off
both my shoes

561
00:49:53,059 --> 00:49:55,459
When they play
theJelly Roll blues

562
00:49:55,528 --> 00:50:00,295
<i>Tomorrow night at the</i>
<i>dark-town strutter's ball</i>

563
00:50:00,366 --> 00:50:03,597
[ Al Auf Singing ]

564
00:50:05,538 --> 00:50:07,836
<i>[ Chanting In Arabic ]</i>

565
00:50:09,709 --> 00:50:12,735
<i>[ Chanting Continues ]</i>

566
00:50:12,812 --> 00:50:15,406
Give me your hand.

567
00:50:17,317 --> 00:50:19,251
Thanks.

568
00:50:19,319 --> 00:50:23,722
<i>[ Chanting Continues ]</i>

569
00:50:27,460 --> 00:50:30,861
[ Chanting Response ]

570
00:50:35,068 --> 00:50:38,128
<i>[ Chanting Continues ]</i>

571
00:51:55,381 --> 00:51:58,111
<i>Madox!</i>

572
00:51:58,184 --> 00:52:00,209
<i>Madox!</i>

573
00:52:00,286 --> 00:52:02,220
<i>Madox!</i>

574
00:52:02,288 --> 00:52:05,655
- Come quickly! I've found something!
- What is it?

575
00:52:05,725 --> 00:52:09,684
D'Ag! Bermann!
Quick!

576
00:52:26,913 --> 00:52:28,904
My God.

577
00:52:30,616 --> 00:52:32,880
They're swimming.

578
00:52:37,924 --> 00:52:40,358
<i>[ Madox ]</i>
<i>They're swimming.</i>

579
00:52:54,907 --> 00:52:58,308
<i>[ Man Talking:Indistinct ]</i>

580
00:52:59,879 --> 00:53:04,179
<i>[ Men Speaking Arabic ]</i>

581
00:53:09,121 --> 00:53:11,180
Ow!

582
00:53:14,026 --> 00:53:17,393
- You okay?
- Yeah.

583
00:53:37,154 --> 00:53:39,588
[ Giggling ]

584
00:53:42,593 --> 00:53:44,754
<i>How do you explain...</i>

585
00:53:44,828 --> 00:53:48,093
to someone who has
never been here,

586
00:53:48,165 --> 00:53:52,693
feelings which seem
quite normal?

587
00:53:55,773 --> 00:53:59,106
I don't know,
my friend.

588
00:53:59,176 --> 00:54:01,701
I don't know.

589
00:54:05,182 --> 00:54:07,480
- Aaah!
- Kamal!

590
00:54:07,551 --> 00:54:09,644
<i>Bermann,</i>
<i>what are you doing?</i>

591
00:54:09,720 --> 00:54:11,847
Bermann!

592
00:54:13,624 --> 00:54:15,819
Watch out!
Watch out!

593
00:54:17,728 --> 00:54:21,494
[ Men Shouting In Arabic ]

594
00:54:25,636 --> 00:54:29,072
- Get them out of the car!
- Let me help!

595
00:54:29,139 --> 00:54:31,505
Almasy,
are you all right?

596
00:54:31,575 --> 00:54:34,635
Yes, yes,
I'm fine.

597
00:54:36,280 --> 00:54:39,306
My wrist!
Ah!

598
00:54:39,383 --> 00:54:43,183
<i>[ Men Speaking Arabic ]</i>

599
00:54:52,996 --> 00:54:57,831
I'll be back as quick as I can,
36 hours at the outside.

600
00:54:57,901 --> 00:55:00,165
Try to get
an additional radiator.

601
00:55:00,237 --> 00:55:05,140
We can store it between here
and Pottery Hill. And a better jack.

602
00:55:05,209 --> 00:55:08,667
- We planned badly.
- Bermann?

603
00:55:09,947 --> 00:55:12,882
<i>[ Engine Starts ]</i>

604
00:55:12,950 --> 00:55:15,544
[ Arabic ]

605
00:55:22,126 --> 00:55:24,026
Safe journey.

606
00:55:26,697 --> 00:55:28,790
Now what?

607
00:55:28,866 --> 00:55:32,097
<i>[ Madox ] Let's get all</i>
<i>this stuff off.</i>

608
00:55:32,169 --> 00:55:35,138
- I'll stay behind, of course.
- Certainly not.

609
00:55:35,205 --> 00:55:38,140
- I caused the problem. I shall stay.
- You can't. None of you can.

610
00:55:38,208 --> 00:55:41,075
<i>No, I insist. There clearly</i>
<i>isn't room for all of us.</i>

611
00:55:41,145 --> 00:55:44,114
I'm the least able to dig, and I'm not
one of the walking wounded.

612
00:55:44,181 --> 00:55:46,115
It's only one night.

613
00:55:46,183 --> 00:55:49,619
If I remain, it's the most effective
method of persuading my husband...

614
00:55:49,686 --> 00:55:53,122
to abandon whatever he's doing
and come and rescue us.

615
00:55:53,190 --> 00:55:55,784
- All right.
- Come on, let's get going.

616
00:55:58,295 --> 00:56:00,889
[ Engine Starts ]

617
00:56:40,037 --> 00:56:43,438
I thought you might like to
paste them into your book.

618
00:56:50,180 --> 00:56:52,648
<i>Well, we</i>--

619
00:56:52,716 --> 00:56:55,184
We took
photographs.

620
00:56:57,387 --> 00:56:59,685
There's no need.

621
00:57:00,824 --> 00:57:03,384
No, really.
I'd like you to have them.

622
00:57:03,460 --> 00:57:05,951
Well, there's really no need.
This is, um--

623
00:57:06,029 --> 00:57:09,829
<i>This is just a scrapbook.</i>
<i>They are too good.</i>

624
00:57:09,900 --> 00:57:13,631
I should feel obliged.
Thank you.

625
00:57:28,285 --> 00:57:31,413
And that would be unconscionable,
I suppose, wouldn't it?

626
00:57:31,488 --> 00:57:34,082
To feel any obligation.

627
00:57:37,294 --> 00:57:40,229
Yes, of course it would.

628
00:57:59,082 --> 00:58:02,017
[ Men Speaking Arabic ]

629
00:58:09,693 --> 00:58:12,218
You should come
into the shelter.

630
00:58:12,296 --> 00:58:14,287
I'm quite all right,
thank you.

631
00:58:14,364 --> 00:58:18,232
- Look over there.
- What am I looking at?

632
00:58:18,302 --> 00:58:20,668
Do you see what's happening to them,
the stars?

633
00:58:20,737 --> 00:58:24,229
- They're so untidy.
I was trying to rearrange them.
- <i>No, no.</i>

634
00:58:24,308 --> 00:58:26,276
Over there.

635
00:58:30,280 --> 00:58:32,874
<i>In a few minutes,</i>
<i>there'll be no stars.</i>

636
00:58:32,949 --> 00:58:35,315
The air
is filling with sand.

637
00:58:41,758 --> 00:58:45,353
[ Wind Howling ]

638
00:58:54,271 --> 00:58:57,365
[ Shouting ]

639
00:59:30,240 --> 00:59:32,333
[ Panting ]

640
00:59:32,409 --> 00:59:35,242
[ Coughing ]

641
00:59:38,448 --> 00:59:42,077
- This is not very good, is it?
- No.

642
00:59:43,487 --> 00:59:45,421
[ Coughing ]

643
00:59:45,489 --> 00:59:49,118
- Will we be all right?
- Yes.

644
00:59:49,192 --> 00:59:51,126
Yes.

645
00:59:52,129 --> 00:59:54,393
Absolutely.

646
00:59:54,464 --> 00:59:57,831
''Yes'' is a comfort.
''Absolutely'' is not.

647
01:00:13,984 --> 01:00:17,351
<i>Let me tell you</i>
<i>about winds.</i>

648
01:00:17,421 --> 01:00:20,288
<i>There is a, a whirlwind</i>
<i>from southern Morocco,</i>

649
01:00:20,357 --> 01:00:22,621
the Aajej,

650
01:00:22,692 --> 01:00:26,458
against which the Fellahin
defend themselves with knives.

651
01:00:28,198 --> 01:00:32,134
And there is a,
a Ghibli from Tunis.

652
01:00:32,202 --> 01:00:34,534
- A Ghibli?
- A Ghibli.

653
01:00:34,604 --> 01:00:38,370
Which rolls and rolls
and rolls and produces a--

654
01:00:38,442 --> 01:00:41,900
- a rather strange nervous condition.
- [ Laughing ]

655
01:00:44,080 --> 01:00:48,107
And then there is the,
the Harmatten,

656
01:00:48,185 --> 01:00:52,986
a red wind, which mariners call
''the sea of darkness.''

657
01:00:54,257 --> 01:00:56,248
And red sand
from this wind...

658
01:00:56,326 --> 01:00:59,227
has flown as far as
the south coast of England,

659
01:00:59,296 --> 01:01:01,730
apparently producing...

660
01:01:01,798 --> 01:01:05,199
showers so dense that they were
mistaken for blood.

661
01:01:05,268 --> 01:01:08,032
Fiction!

662
01:01:08,104 --> 01:01:12,131
We have a house on that coast
and it has never, never rained blood.

663
01:01:12,209 --> 01:01:15,144
No, it's all true.
Herodotus, your friend.

664
01:01:15,212 --> 01:01:17,476
- My friend.
- Your fri--

665
01:01:17,547 --> 01:01:20,141
He writes about it...

666
01:01:20,217 --> 01:01:23,675
and he writes about...

667
01:01:23,753 --> 01:01:27,154
a, a wind, the Simoon,

668
01:01:27,224 --> 01:01:29,920
which a nation thought
was so evil,

669
01:01:29,993 --> 01:01:33,429
they declared war on it
and marched out against it.

670
01:01:34,798 --> 01:01:37,130
In full battle dress.

671
01:01:39,336 --> 01:01:42,203
<i>Their swords raised.</i>

672
01:02:01,958 --> 01:02:06,452
<i>[ Engine Running,</i>
<i>Horn Honking ]</i>

673
01:02:06,530 --> 01:02:10,466
Katharine, Katharine, I need
to get out your side, quickly.

674
01:02:10,534 --> 01:02:12,900
A car!
Let me out!

675
01:02:12,969 --> 01:02:15,733
Of course.
I'm sorry.

676
01:02:15,805 --> 01:02:18,035
Ridiculous
to fall asleep!

677
01:02:18,108 --> 01:02:20,167
Unforgivable!

678
01:02:20,243 --> 01:02:22,677
Damn!
The flare!

679
01:02:24,047 --> 01:02:25,981
Stop!
Over here!

680
01:02:26,049 --> 01:02:28,279
- [ Honking ]
- <i>Here!</i>

681
01:02:28,351 --> 01:02:30,842
- Stop!
-<i>[ Honking ]</i>

682
01:02:30,921 --> 01:02:34,049
- Madox!
- [ Flare Gun Fires ]

683
01:02:34,124 --> 01:02:37,525
<i>Madox! Madox!</i>

684
01:02:51,041 --> 01:02:53,236
Our tracks
have disappeared.

685
01:02:53,310 --> 01:02:56,802
Madox will calculate how many miles.
He'll soon turn around.

686
01:03:01,785 --> 01:03:04,754
Could I ask you,
please, to...

687
01:03:04,821 --> 01:03:08,257
paste your paintings
into my book.

688
01:03:08,325 --> 01:03:10,520
<i>I</i>-- <i>I should like</i>
<i>to have them.</i>

689
01:03:10,594 --> 01:03:13,062
I should be honored.

690
01:03:15,732 --> 01:03:18,895
-<i>[ Muffled Honking ]</i>
- The others!

691
01:03:20,070 --> 01:03:22,561
- Oh, God.
- <i>Quick!</i>

692
01:03:22,639 --> 01:03:25,301
<i>[ Honking Continues ]</i>

693
01:03:26,676 --> 01:03:30,510
Oh, how awful!
We've got to get them out.

694
01:03:30,580 --> 01:03:33,310
Quick!
Get the other shovel!

695
01:03:33,383 --> 01:03:36,375
<i>[ Honking Continues ]</i>

696
01:03:36,453 --> 01:03:39,889
Am I a terrible coward
to ask how much water we have left?

697
01:03:39,956 --> 01:03:43,915
A little in our can. We have, uh, water
in the radiator, which can be drunk.

698
01:03:43,994 --> 01:03:48,192
And, uh, that's not cowardly at all.
It's extremely practical.

699
01:03:48,264 --> 01:03:51,631
We, uh-- Oh, come on!
Come on!

700
01:03:51,701 --> 01:03:55,728
-<i>[ Honking Continues ]</i>
- There's also a plant.

701
01:03:55,805 --> 01:04:00,174
I've never seen it,
but I believe you can cut a piece
the size of a heart from this plant,

702
01:04:00,243 --> 01:04:03,679
and the next morning it'll be filled
with a delicious liquid.

703
01:04:03,747 --> 01:04:07,581
Find that plant,
cut out its heart.

704
01:04:07,651 --> 01:04:11,451
<i>[ Honking Continues ]</i>

705
01:04:11,521 --> 01:04:14,456
Here.

706
01:04:17,060 --> 01:04:19,722
<i>[ Men Shouting ]</i>

707
01:04:19,796 --> 01:04:22,162
Here's the window.

708
01:04:22,232 --> 01:04:25,201
<i>Clear the glass. I'll clear the door.</i>
<i>Mind your hands.</i>

709
01:04:25,268 --> 01:04:28,328
- [ Shouting ]
- It's okay. We're here.

710
01:04:28,405 --> 01:04:30,965
Come on,
clear it quickly.

711
01:04:31,041 --> 01:04:32,975
<i>[ Shouting ]</i>

712
01:04:33,043 --> 01:04:36,035
Hang on.
Coming.

713
01:04:40,250 --> 01:04:44,311
[ Shouting In Arabic ]

714
01:04:44,387 --> 01:04:48,517
- I've got it. I've got it.
- Help them out. Here.

715
01:05:07,110 --> 01:05:09,635
[ Arabic ]

716
01:05:58,728 --> 01:06:01,094
<i>Katharine.</i>

717
01:06:05,935 --> 01:06:07,869
<i>Water.</i>

718
01:06:14,110 --> 01:06:17,443
[ Flare Fires, Explodes ]

719
01:06:24,120 --> 01:06:26,418
<i>[ Katharine ]</i>
<i>Geoffrey's not in Cairo.</i>

720
01:06:29,826 --> 01:06:32,659
He's not actually
a buffoon.

721
01:06:32,729 --> 01:06:34,720
The plane wasn't
a wedding present.

722
01:06:34,798 --> 01:06:37,494
It belongs
to the British government.

723
01:06:37,567 --> 01:06:40,934
They want aerial maps
of the whole of North Africa.

724
01:06:41,004 --> 01:06:43,768
So I think
he's in Ethiopia.

725
01:06:45,842 --> 01:06:49,039
In case you're counting
on his sudden appearance.

726
01:06:53,082 --> 01:06:55,710
And the marriage.

727
01:06:55,785 --> 01:06:58,049
Is that a fiction?

728
01:07:00,523 --> 01:07:03,117
No, the marriage
isn't a fiction.

729
01:07:05,495 --> 01:07:08,055
<i>[ Men Shouting In Arabic ]</i>

730
01:07:08,131 --> 01:07:11,191
- Oh, thank God.
-<i>[ Shouting Continues ]</i>

731
01:07:11,267 --> 01:07:13,292
Thank God.

732
01:07:13,369 --> 01:07:16,429
Madox.
It's Madox.

733
01:07:16,506 --> 01:07:19,839
[ Shouting ]

734
01:07:21,644 --> 01:07:24,511
Am I K. in your book?

735
01:07:24,581 --> 01:07:26,845
I think I must be.

736
01:07:49,539 --> 01:07:51,530
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>Chapter one.</i>

737
01:07:51,608 --> 01:07:56,238
<i>''He sat in defiance of municipal orders</i>
<i>astride the gun Zamzammah</i>--<i>''</i>

738
01:07:56,312 --> 01:07:59,873
<i>I can't read these words. I can't</i>
<i>read them. They stick in my throat.</i>

739
01:07:59,949 --> 01:08:02,349
<i>[ Almasy ] Because you're</i>
<i>reading it too fast.</i>

740
01:08:02,418 --> 01:08:05,216
- Not at all.
- <i>You have to read Kipling slowly.</i>

741
01:08:05,288 --> 01:08:09,122
<i>Your eye is too impatient.</i>
<i>Think about the speed ofhis pen.</i>

742
01:08:09,192 --> 01:08:12,218
What is it?
''He sat, comma,

743
01:08:12,295 --> 01:08:15,492
<i>''in defiance of</i>
<i>municipal orders, comma,</i>

744
01:08:15,565 --> 01:08:18,534
''astride the gun
Zamzammah...

745
01:08:18,601 --> 01:08:22,367
on her brick--''
What is it?

746
01:08:22,438 --> 01:08:25,271
''Brick platform, opposite the old
Ajaib-Gher.''

747
01:08:25,341 --> 01:08:30,176
<i>''The wonder house, comma,</i>

748
01:08:30,246 --> 01:08:33,841
as the natives called
the Lahore Museum.''

749
01:08:33,917 --> 01:08:37,182
<i>It's still there, the cannon,</i>
<i>outside the museum.</i>

750
01:08:37,253 --> 01:08:41,053
Made of metal cups and bowls taken
from every household in the city as tax,

751
01:08:41,124 --> 01:08:43,388
then melted down.

752
01:08:43,459 --> 01:08:47,520
Then later, they fired
the cannon at my people,

753
01:08:47,597 --> 01:08:51,363
comma,
the natives.

754
01:08:51,434 --> 01:08:53,368
Full stop.

755
01:08:53,436 --> 01:08:55,370
[ Slurping ]

756
01:08:55,438 --> 01:08:57,372
What exactly
is it you object to?

757
01:08:57,440 --> 01:09:00,341
The writer,
or what he's writing about?

758
01:09:00,410 --> 01:09:04,278
What I really
object to, Uncle,

759
01:09:04,347 --> 01:09:06,645
is your finishing
all my condensed milk.

760
01:09:06,716 --> 01:09:09,651
And the message everywhere in your book,
however slowly I read it,

761
01:09:09,719 --> 01:09:12,847
that the best thing for India
is to be ruled by the British.

762
01:09:12,922 --> 01:09:16,289
Hana, we have discovered
a shared pleasure, the boy and I.

763
01:09:16,359 --> 01:09:18,919
- Arguing about books?
- <i>Condensed milk.</i>

764
01:09:18,995 --> 01:09:21,225
One of the truly
great inventions.

765
01:09:21,297 --> 01:09:24,198
I'll get
another tin.

766
01:09:24,267 --> 01:09:27,896
I didn't like that book either.
It's all about men.

767
01:09:27,971 --> 01:09:31,429
Too many men.
Just like this house.

768
01:09:31,507 --> 01:09:34,943
You like him, don't you?
Your voice changes.

769
01:09:35,011 --> 01:09:37,445
No, I don't
think it does.

770
01:09:37,513 --> 01:09:40,004
Anyway,
he's indifferent to me.

771
01:09:40,083 --> 01:09:43,211
<i>I don't think</i>
<i>it's indifference.</i>

772
01:09:43,286 --> 01:09:45,777
- <i>Hana was just telling me,</i>
<i>you're indifferent...</i>
- Hey!

773
01:09:45,855 --> 01:09:47,948
to her cooking.

774
01:09:49,425 --> 01:09:51,416
Well, I'm indifferent
to cooking.

775
01:09:51,494 --> 01:09:54,292
Not Hana's cooking
in particular.

776
01:09:54,364 --> 01:09:57,629
Have either of you tried
condensed milk sandwiches?

777
01:09:57,700 --> 01:09:59,634
[ Coughing ]

778
01:09:59,702 --> 01:10:02,603
They're very good
with salt.

779
01:10:02,672 --> 01:10:06,506
<i>[ Horns Honking ]</i>

780
01:10:06,576 --> 01:10:09,443
[ People Chattering ]

781
01:10:09,512 --> 01:10:12,106
[ Honking ]

782
01:10:23,159 --> 01:10:25,423
Welcome back, Madam.

783
01:10:38,107 --> 01:10:40,098
Will you not come in?

784
01:10:40,176 --> 01:10:42,371
No.

785
01:10:42,445 --> 01:10:45,505
- <i>I should go home.</i>
- Will you please come in?

786
01:10:46,716 --> 01:10:48,650
Mrs. Clifton.

787
01:10:51,154 --> 01:10:53,782
Don't.

788
01:10:53,856 --> 01:10:55,824
I believe
you still have my book.

789
01:11:11,874 --> 01:11:13,899
Thank you.

790
01:11:25,488 --> 01:11:28,457
<i>[ Chanting In Distance ]</i>

791
01:11:33,663 --> 01:11:35,756
<i>[ Knocking ]</i>

792
01:11:39,602 --> 01:11:41,536
<i>[ Knocking ]</i>

793
01:11:48,911 --> 01:11:50,970
<i>[ Hinges Creak ]</i>

794
01:12:38,094 --> 01:12:41,029
You still have
sand in your hair.

795
01:13:04,453 --> 01:13:07,388
It wouldn't be
make-believe

796
01:13:07,456 --> 01:13:10,857
If you believe in me

797
01:13:10,927 --> 01:13:14,419
Without your love

798
01:13:14,497 --> 01:13:16,863
I'm impressed
you can sew.

799
01:13:16,933 --> 01:13:18,867
Good.

800
01:13:25,942 --> 01:13:28,570
You sew very badly.

801
01:13:28,644 --> 01:13:30,976
Well, you don't
sew at all.

802
01:13:31,047 --> 01:13:32,981
A woman should
never learn to sew,

803
01:13:33,049 --> 01:13:35,643
and if she can,
she shouldn't admit to it.

804
01:13:35,718 --> 01:13:37,811
[ Snickers ]

805
01:13:43,426 --> 01:13:46,452
Close your eyes.

806
01:13:46,529 --> 01:13:49,555
It makes it harder still.

807
01:13:52,368 --> 01:13:54,302
Hmm.

808
01:13:57,773 --> 01:14:00,037
When were you
most happy?

809
01:14:00,109 --> 01:14:02,805
Now.

810
01:14:04,180 --> 01:14:06,478
And when were you
least happy?

811
01:14:09,051 --> 01:14:11,042
Now.

812
01:14:15,958 --> 01:14:17,823
- What do you love?
- What do I love?

813
01:14:17,893 --> 01:14:21,920
- Say everything.
- Let's see.

814
01:14:21,998 --> 01:14:24,091
- Water.
- <i>Mm-hmm.</i>

815
01:14:24,166 --> 01:14:26,327
<i>[ Water Splashing ]</i>

816
01:14:26,402 --> 01:14:29,098
- Fish in it.
-<i>[ Chuckles ]</i>

817
01:14:29,171 --> 01:14:32,072
And hedgehogs.
I love hedgehogs.

818
01:14:32,141 --> 01:14:34,075
And what else?

819
01:14:34,143 --> 01:14:37,078
Marmite.
I'm addicted.

820
01:14:38,848 --> 01:14:42,147
And baths.
But not with other people.

821
01:14:42,218 --> 01:14:44,482
[ Laughing ]

822
01:14:46,856 --> 01:14:48,915
Islands.

823
01:14:51,027 --> 01:14:53,461
And your handwriting.

824
01:14:55,431 --> 01:14:58,457
- Mmm.
- I could go on all day.

825
01:14:58,534 --> 01:15:00,525
Go on all day.

826
01:15:08,544 --> 01:15:10,876
My husband.

827
01:15:12,815 --> 01:15:15,249
And what do you
hate most?

828
01:15:18,888 --> 01:15:21,152
A lie.

829
01:15:22,458 --> 01:15:25,655
What do you
hate most?

830
01:15:28,898 --> 01:15:31,492
Ownership.

831
01:15:31,567 --> 01:15:33,660
Being owned.

832
01:15:34,837 --> 01:15:37,601
When you leave,
you should forget me.

833
01:16:07,737 --> 01:16:11,195
-<i>[ Hana ] Who is this?</i>
-<i>[ Almasy ] Don't you recognize me?</i>

834
01:16:11,273 --> 01:16:15,004
[ Laughing ]
Is it you? So fat.

835
01:16:15,077 --> 01:16:17,341
<i>[ Chuckles ]</i>

836
01:16:20,116 --> 01:16:22,380
- Hmm.
- <i>That's a Christmas cracker.</i>

837
01:16:22,451 --> 01:16:24,544
<i>Firecracker.</i>

838
01:16:24,620 --> 01:16:27,555
- This isn't your handwriting, is it?
- <i>Yes, it is.</i>

839
01:16:29,125 --> 01:16:31,889
''December 22nd.

840
01:16:31,961 --> 01:16:35,453
''Betrayals in war
are childlike...

841
01:16:35,531 --> 01:16:38,694
''compared with our
betrayals during peace.

842
01:16:38,768 --> 01:16:43,034
''New lovers are nervous
and tender...

843
01:16:44,173 --> 01:16:46,437
''but smash everything.

844
01:16:46,509 --> 01:16:51,572
<i>For the heart</i>
<i>is an organ of fire. ''</i>

845
01:16:54,250 --> 01:16:57,276
''For the heart
is an organ of fire.''

846
01:17:01,690 --> 01:17:04,955
I love that.

847
01:17:05,027 --> 01:17:07,018
I believe that.

848
01:17:08,330 --> 01:17:10,264
K?

849
01:17:11,634 --> 01:17:14,569
- Who is K?
- <i>K...</i>

850
01:17:15,871 --> 01:17:18,305
is for Katharine.

851
01:17:22,411 --> 01:17:23,742
[ People Chattering ]

852
01:17:28,951 --> 01:17:31,044
Merry Christmas!
Merry Christmas!

853
01:17:37,026 --> 01:17:40,257
- Say you're sick.
- What? No.

854
01:17:40,329 --> 01:17:43,298
Say you're feeling faint.
The heat.

855
01:17:43,365 --> 01:17:46,232
- No.
- I can't work.

856
01:17:46,302 --> 01:17:50,568
- I can't sleep.
- <i>Katharine.</i>

857
01:17:50,639 --> 01:17:52,800
Coming.

858
01:17:54,343 --> 01:17:57,676
I can't sleep. I wake up shouting
in the middle of the night.

859
01:17:57,746 --> 01:18:02,080
- Geoffrey thinks it's the
thing in the desert, trauma.
- I can still taste you.

860
01:18:05,654 --> 01:18:08,623
- Fill up this. It's empty.
- Oh.

861
01:18:08,691 --> 01:18:12,559
I try to write,
with your taste in my mouth.

862
01:18:15,831 --> 01:18:18,766
Swoon.

863
01:18:18,834 --> 01:18:21,462
They'll catch you.

864
01:18:24,173 --> 01:18:27,438
- Ho, ho, ho, ho, ho!
- [ Child Yelling ]

865
01:18:27,510 --> 01:18:30,536
<i>[ Santa Shouting ]</i>

866
01:18:30,613 --> 01:18:34,515
<i>[ Santa Laughing ]</i>

867
01:18:37,386 --> 01:18:40,617
- Come along with me now!
- Merry Christmas, everyone!

868
01:18:40,689 --> 01:18:42,680
Merry Christmas!

869
01:18:42,758 --> 01:18:45,693
- <i>Katharine! Oh, my goodness!</i>
- Oh.

870
01:18:45,761 --> 01:18:47,786
<i>[ Woman ]</i>
<i>Fetch a chair.</i>

871
01:18:47,863 --> 01:18:49,831
No, I'm fine.

872
01:18:49,899 --> 01:18:52,163
- It's this heat. It's terrible.
- Is she all right?

873
01:18:52,234 --> 01:18:55,067
- She's quite all right.
- Oh, good.

874
01:18:55,137 --> 01:18:57,901
- Are you pregnant?
- Oh, I don't think so, no.

875
01:18:57,973 --> 01:18:59,964
[ Laughing ]
How romantic.

876
01:19:00,042 --> 01:19:02,374
With Fiona, I fell over
every five minutes.

877
01:19:02,444 --> 01:19:05,538
Ronnie christened me
''Lady Downfall.''

878
01:19:05,614 --> 01:19:09,778
Do you know, I think I might go inside
and sit down for a few minutes.

879
01:19:09,852 --> 01:19:12,946
- I'll come with you.
- No, I'll be all right. You stay here.

880
01:19:13,022 --> 01:19:15,354
Are you sure?

881
01:19:56,498 --> 01:20:01,060
<i>[ Bagpipes ]</i>

882
01:20:01,136 --> 01:20:05,573
<i>Silent night</i>

883
01:20:05,641 --> 01:20:09,941
<i>Holy night</i>

884
01:20:10,012 --> 01:20:13,914
<i>All is calm</i>

885
01:20:13,983 --> 01:20:18,682
<i>All is bright</i>

886
01:20:18,754 --> 01:20:23,384
<i>Round yon virgin</i>

887
01:20:23,459 --> 01:20:26,394
<i>And her child</i>

888
01:20:39,708 --> 01:20:45,044
Silent night

889
01:20:45,114 --> 01:20:49,107
Holy night

890
01:20:49,184 --> 01:20:54,417
<i>All is calm</i>

891
01:20:54,490 --> 01:20:58,517
<i>All is bright</i>

892
01:21:28,424 --> 01:21:35,626
Sleep in heavenly peace

893
01:21:38,567 --> 01:21:41,161
[ All ]
Happy Christmas!

894
01:21:43,539 --> 01:21:47,999
[ Men ]  God save our
gracious king

895
01:21:48,077 --> 01:21:50,773
- Have you seen Katharine?
- What?

896
01:21:50,846 --> 01:21:53,110
- It's Clifton under here.
- <i>Oh.</i>

897
01:21:53,182 --> 01:21:56,049
- No, I haven't. Sorry.
- [ Sighs ]

898
01:21:57,119 --> 01:22:01,021
<i>Send him victorious</i>

899
01:22:01,090 --> 01:22:04,287
Darling,
I just heard.

900
01:22:05,961 --> 01:22:08,395
You poor sausage.
Are you all right?

901
01:22:08,464 --> 01:22:11,058
I'm fine.
I'm just too hot.

902
01:22:11,133 --> 01:22:13,601
Lady H thought you
might be pregnant.

903
01:22:13,669 --> 01:22:17,662
I'm not pregnant. I'm just hot.
Too hot, like you.

904
01:22:17,740 --> 01:22:20,709
I'm sweltering,
in fact.

905
01:22:23,312 --> 01:22:26,577
Come on,
I'll take you home.

906
01:22:26,648 --> 01:22:31,210
Can we really go home?
I can't breathe.

907
01:22:31,286 --> 01:22:35,154
<i>I am dying for green.</i>
<i>Anything green, or rain.</i>

908
01:22:35,224 --> 01:22:40,355
It's Christmas and it's all--
Oh, I don't know.

909
01:22:45,000 --> 01:22:49,096
If you asked me, I'd go home tomorrow.
If you wanted.

910
01:22:49,171 --> 01:22:53,130
Darling, you know we can't go home.
There might be a war.

911
01:22:58,447 --> 01:23:01,883
Oh, Geoffrey,
you do so love a disguise.

912
01:23:01,950 --> 01:23:03,941
I do so love you.

913
01:23:06,388 --> 01:23:08,322
Mmm.

914
01:23:09,591 --> 01:23:12,526
- What do you smell of?
- What?

915
01:23:14,530 --> 01:23:18,796
Marzipan. I think you've
got marzipan in your hair.

916
01:23:18,867 --> 01:23:21,358
No wonder
you're homesick.

917
01:23:22,437 --> 01:23:25,838
<i>[ Thunder Rumbling ]</i>

918
01:23:28,777 --> 01:23:31,371
[ Breathing Heavily ]

919
01:23:43,058 --> 01:23:44,992
Is it you?

920
01:23:46,061 --> 01:23:47,494
What?

921
01:23:48,797 --> 01:23:50,788
If I said ''Moose''--

922
01:23:50,866 --> 01:23:53,835
Moose?
Who the hell's Moose?

923
01:23:56,672 --> 01:23:58,731
I look different.

924
01:23:58,807 --> 01:24:01,241
Why shouldn't you?

925
01:24:04,847 --> 01:24:07,247
<i>[ Thunder Rumbling ]</i>

926
01:24:07,316 --> 01:24:09,375
<i>I heard your breathing.</i>

927
01:24:09,451 --> 01:24:13,410
I thought it was the rain.
I'm dying for rain.

928
01:24:13,488 --> 01:24:16,719
Well, I'm dying anyway,
but I--

929
01:24:16,792 --> 01:24:20,125
I long for
the rain on my face.

930
01:24:20,195 --> 01:24:23,221
First wedding anniversary,
what do you call it?

931
01:24:23,298 --> 01:24:26,756
Ha, I don't know.
Paper?

932
01:24:26,835 --> 01:24:30,134
<i>Is it?</i>
<i>I don't know.</i>

933
01:24:30,205 --> 01:24:32,139
Paper.

934
01:24:32,207 --> 01:24:34,573
-<i>[ Typewriter Clicking ]</i>
- Paper?

935
01:24:34,643 --> 01:24:36,804
Darling, it's me.
Listen, I'm sorry, something's come up.

936
01:24:36,879 --> 01:24:39,507
- Oh, no.
- Now don't sulk.
I'll be back tomorrow evening.

937
01:24:39,581 --> 01:24:42,414
I'm going to sulk, and I'm not moving
till you get back here.

938
01:24:42,484 --> 01:24:44,509
Promise?
That's good.

939
01:24:44,586 --> 01:24:47,020
Okay, my sausage,
I love you.

940
01:24:50,025 --> 01:24:52,960
- I didn't know you were going anywhere.
- I'm not.

941
01:24:53,028 --> 01:24:57,431
I'm going to surprise her. It's our
anniversary. She's forgotten, of course.

942
01:24:57,499 --> 01:24:59,899
What's the symbol of your first
anniversary? I should get something.

943
01:24:59,968 --> 01:25:01,936
<i>Is it cotton or paper?</i>

944
01:25:02,004 --> 01:25:05,064
Your first anniversary? I thought you
two'd been married for donkey's years.

945
01:25:05,140 --> 01:25:08,405
We've been friends for donkey's years.
Best friends.

946
01:25:08,477 --> 01:25:11,412
She was always crying on
my shoulder about somebody.

947
01:25:11,480 --> 01:25:15,416
I finally persuaded her to settle
for my shoulder. A stroke of genius.

948
01:25:17,819 --> 01:25:20,879
- Moose, are you there?
- <i>Yes.</i>

949
01:25:20,956 --> 01:25:24,892
- First anniversary. Is that cotton?
- Uh, is what cotton?

950
01:25:24,960 --> 01:25:27,724
First wedding anniversary.

951
01:25:27,796 --> 01:25:30,492
Your first anniversary
is... paper.

952
01:25:43,478 --> 01:25:46,606
- Stop.
- Please?

953
01:25:46,682 --> 01:25:48,673
S-- Stop here.

954
01:25:48,750 --> 01:25:51,014
- Here?
-<i>Just stop right here.</i>

955
01:25:51,086 --> 01:25:53,213
Yes, sir.

956
01:25:53,288 --> 01:25:56,553
<i>[ Katharine Speaking Arabic ]</i>

957
01:26:06,535 --> 01:26:09,732
<i>[ Chanting In Distance ]</i>

958
01:26:16,912 --> 01:26:21,474
[ Phonograph Plays
Foreign Song ]

959
01:26:29,257 --> 01:26:31,589
This--
What is this?

960
01:26:33,061 --> 01:26:35,495
-  [ Continues ]
- It's a folk song.

961
01:26:35,564 --> 01:26:38,624
-<i>Arabic.</i>
- No, no, it's Hungarian.

962
01:26:40,602 --> 01:26:43,093
My <i>daijka</i> sang it to me.

963
01:26:43,171 --> 01:26:46,902
When I was a child
growing up in Budapest.

964
01:26:53,915 --> 01:26:55,906
It's beautiful.

965
01:26:55,984 --> 01:26:58,145
Hmm.

966
01:26:58,220 --> 01:27:00,586
What's it about?

967
01:27:00,655 --> 01:27:02,646
<i>Szerelem</i> means love.

968
01:27:02,724 --> 01:27:05,955
And the story--
Well, there's, um,

969
01:27:06,028 --> 01:27:08,588
this Hungarian count.

970
01:27:08,663 --> 01:27:10,654
He's a wanderer.
He's a fool.

971
01:27:10,732 --> 01:27:14,930
<i>And for years he's on</i>
<i>some kind of a quest for...</i>

972
01:27:15,003 --> 01:27:17,437
who knows what.

973
01:27:17,506 --> 01:27:23,308
And then one day, he falls under
the spell of a mysterious English woman,

974
01:27:23,378 --> 01:27:27,109
a harpy, who beats him
and hits him.

975
01:27:27,182 --> 01:27:30,777
And he becomes her slave
and he sews her clothes and worships--

976
01:27:30,852 --> 01:27:32,843
Stop!
Stop it!

977
01:27:32,921 --> 01:27:35,515
Stop! You're always
beating me.

978
01:27:35,590 --> 01:27:37,615
- Bastard.
- [ Laughing ]

979
01:27:37,692 --> 01:27:39,990
You bastard!
I believed you!

980
01:27:40,062 --> 01:27:43,463
You should be
my slave.

981
01:27:43,532 --> 01:27:47,662
<i>[ Song Continues ]</i>

982
01:27:49,071 --> 01:27:53,804
I claim this
shoulder blade--

983
01:27:53,875 --> 01:27:57,675
No, wait. No, I want--
Turn over.

984
01:27:57,746 --> 01:28:01,739
I want this, this--
this place.

985
01:28:04,219 --> 01:28:06,881
I love this place.
What's it called?

986
01:28:09,591 --> 01:28:12,458
This is mine.

987
01:28:12,527 --> 01:28:16,861
I'm going to ask the king permission
to call it the Almasy Bosphorus.

988
01:28:16,932 --> 01:28:19,958
[ Giggling ]

989
01:28:20,035 --> 01:28:23,163
I thought we were
against ownership.

990
01:28:31,813 --> 01:28:34,213
I can stay tonight.

991
01:28:40,522 --> 01:28:42,683
Madox knows,
I think.

992
01:28:42,757 --> 01:28:45,419
He keeps talking about
Anna Karenina.

993
01:28:45,494 --> 01:28:49,055
I think it's his idea
of a man-to-man chat.

994
01:28:49,131 --> 01:28:51,861
Well, it's my idea
of a man-to-man chat.

995
01:28:55,036 --> 01:28:57,470
<i>[ Song Continues ]</i>

996
01:28:57,539 --> 01:29:00,906
This is a different world,
is what I tell myself.

997
01:29:04,079 --> 01:29:06,513
A different life.

998
01:29:08,250 --> 01:29:11,777
And here
I'm a different wife.

999
01:29:14,456 --> 01:29:16,981
Yes.

1000
01:29:17,058 --> 01:29:20,550
Here you are
a different wife.

1001
01:29:25,167 --> 01:29:28,694
<i>[ Song Continues ]</i>

1002
01:29:56,932 --> 01:29:59,867
Oh, they're darling.
What are they? Thimbles?

1003
01:29:59,935 --> 01:30:03,029
Yes, and they're
quite old.

1004
01:30:03,104 --> 01:30:05,231
It's full of saffron.

1005
01:30:05,307 --> 01:30:09,004
Just in case you think
I'm going to give it to you
to encourage your sewing.

1006
01:30:10,979 --> 01:30:13,140
[ Arabic ]

1007
01:30:16,718 --> 01:30:19,152
I don't care
to bargain.

1008
01:30:20,622 --> 01:30:23,284
That day, did you follow me
to the market?

1009
01:30:23,358 --> 01:30:25,622
Yes, of course.

1010
01:30:31,733 --> 01:30:34,395
Shall we be
all right?

1011
01:30:34,469 --> 01:30:36,403
Yes.

1012
01:30:37,405 --> 01:30:39,339
Yes.

1013
01:30:41,943 --> 01:30:43,934
Absolutely.

1014
01:30:44,012 --> 01:30:45,946
Oh, dear.

1015
01:30:47,282 --> 01:30:50,581
<i>As dancing</i>
<i>cheek to cheek</i>

1016
01:30:50,652 --> 01:30:53,587
<i>Oh, I love to go out fishing</i>

1017
01:30:53,655 --> 01:30:56,488
<i>[ People Chattering ]</i>

1018
01:30:56,558 --> 01:30:59,721
<i>But I don't enjoy it</i>
<i>half as much</i>

1019
01:30:59,794 --> 01:31:02,854
<i>As dancing cheek to cheek</i>

1020
01:31:02,931 --> 01:31:05,331
<i>Dance with me</i>

1021
01:31:05,400 --> 01:31:08,233
-<i>I want my arms about you</i>
- [ Sighs ]

1022
01:31:08,303 --> 01:31:11,363
<i>The charm about you</i>

1023
01:31:11,439 --> 01:31:16,001
<i>Will carry me through</i>
<i>to heaven</i>

1024
01:31:16,077 --> 01:31:19,672
<i>I'm in heaven</i>

1025
01:31:19,748 --> 01:31:26,051
<i>And my heart beats</i>
<i>so that I can hardly speak</i>

1026
01:31:29,024 --> 01:31:32,050
<i>And I seem to find</i>
<i>the happiness I seek</i>

1027
01:31:32,093 --> 01:31:37,554
When we're off together
dancing cheek to cheek

1028
01:31:39,434 --> 01:31:42,631
- Thought you'd never wake up.
- What?

1029
01:31:43,905 --> 01:31:46,601
- Where did you find that?
- I liberated it.

1030
01:31:46,675 --> 01:31:51,271
- I think that's called looting.
- No one should own music.
The real question is:

1031
01:31:51,346 --> 01:31:52,779
- Who wrote the song?
- Irving Berlin.

1032
01:31:52,847 --> 01:31:54,280
- For?
- <i>Top Hat.</i>

1033
01:31:54,349 --> 01:31:56,579
Is there a song
you don't know?

1034
01:31:56,651 --> 01:31:59,950
<i>Nope.</i>
<i>He sings all the time.</i>

1035
01:32:00,021 --> 01:32:03,752
Good morning. Did you know that?
You're always singing.

1036
01:32:03,825 --> 01:32:06,692
I've been told before.

1037
01:32:06,761 --> 01:32:10,288
Kip's another one.

1038
01:32:10,365 --> 01:32:14,233
[ Kip Humming ]

1039
01:32:14,302 --> 01:32:16,930
-<i>[Jazz Clarinet ]</i>
- ''Wang Wang Blues.''

1040
01:32:17,005 --> 01:32:18,768
You're incredible.

1041
01:32:22,177 --> 01:32:25,613
[ Humming ]

1042
01:32:27,382 --> 01:32:29,646
- Good mornin', Miss.
- Hello.

1043
01:32:29,718 --> 01:32:32,482
<i>You saved my life.</i>

1044
01:32:32,554 --> 01:32:36,115
- I haven't forgotten.
- [ Scoffs ]

1045
01:32:36,191 --> 01:32:38,955
<i>I thought you were</i>
<i>very, very tall.</i>

1046
01:32:39,027 --> 01:32:43,191
You seemed so big
and... giant.

1047
01:32:43,264 --> 01:32:45,960
I felt like a child
who can't keep her balance.

1048
01:32:46,034 --> 01:32:49,834
- A toddler.
- A toddler.

1049
01:32:49,904 --> 01:32:52,839
<i>[Jazz Continues ]</i>

1050
01:32:54,743 --> 01:32:57,610
[ Giggles ]

1051
01:33:04,819 --> 01:33:07,754
[ Humming ]

1052
01:33:10,358 --> 01:33:13,521
<i>[ Humming Continues ]</i>

1053
01:33:13,595 --> 01:33:16,029
My hair was long
at some point.

1054
01:33:19,300 --> 01:33:23,566
I've forgotten what
a nuisance it is to wash.

1055
01:33:25,874 --> 01:33:29,002
Try this. I found
a great jar of it.

1056
01:33:29,077 --> 01:33:31,011
Olive oil.

1057
01:33:31,079 --> 01:33:33,013
Thank you.

1058
01:33:41,556 --> 01:33:44,389
Is this for my hair?

1059
01:33:44,459 --> 01:33:47,553
Yes, for your hair.

1060
01:33:47,629 --> 01:33:50,723
<i>[Jazz Continues ]</i>

1061
01:33:55,637 --> 01:33:58,333
There was a general
who wore a patch...

1062
01:33:58,406 --> 01:34:01,273
over a perfectly
good eye.

1063
01:34:01,342 --> 01:34:04,470
<i>The men fought</i>
<i>harder for him.</i>

1064
01:34:04,546 --> 01:34:07,709
<i>[Jazz Continues ]</i>

1065
01:34:10,185 --> 01:34:13,586
Sometimes I think
I could get up and dance.

1066
01:34:14,722 --> 01:34:16,883
What's under
your mittens?

1067
01:34:22,997 --> 01:34:25,022
What's under
your mittens?

1068
01:34:33,274 --> 01:34:37,142
<i>[ Air Raid Siren ]</i>

1069
01:34:47,121 --> 01:34:49,555
He's waiting for you.

1070
01:34:49,624 --> 01:34:51,114
I'll see you
tonight?

1071
01:34:51,192 --> 01:34:53,990
<i>[ Explosions ]</i>

1072
01:34:54,062 --> 01:34:56,360
Look, Moose, we need you
to stay in Tobruk.

1073
01:34:56,431 --> 01:35:00,458
I know it's a bit of a short straw,
butJerry's got our maps, you know.

1074
01:35:00,535 --> 01:35:03,402
And now they're getting
their spies into Cairo using our maps.

1075
01:35:03,471 --> 01:35:06,133
They'll get Rommel into Cairo
using our maps.

1076
01:35:06,207 --> 01:35:09,802
The whole of the desert's like a bloody
bus route, and we gave it to 'em!

1077
01:35:09,878 --> 01:35:11,812
Any foreigner
who turned up:

1078
01:35:11,880 --> 01:35:14,440
''Welcome to the Royal Geographic.
Take our maps.''

1079
01:35:14,516 --> 01:35:16,450
Old Madox went mad,
you know.

1080
01:35:16,518 --> 01:35:18,577
- Did you know Peter Madox?
- Yeah.

1081
01:35:18,653 --> 01:35:21,247
Magnificent explorer.
Thanks, Aicha.

1082
01:35:21,322 --> 01:35:23,984
And after he found out
he'd been betrayed by Almasy.

1083
01:35:24,058 --> 01:35:26,322
His best friend.

1084
01:35:26,394 --> 01:35:29,124
Absolutely destroyed
the poor sot.

1085
01:35:29,197 --> 01:35:32,132
[ Explosions,
Machine Gun Fire ]

1086
01:35:32,200 --> 01:35:35,135
[ Shouting ]

1087
01:35:36,204 --> 01:35:39,367
[ Shouting In German ]

1088
01:35:43,111 --> 01:35:46,547
<i>[ Shouting Continues ]</i>

1089
01:35:48,850 --> 01:35:51,114
<i>[ Man ] Hey, Commandant,</i>
<i>stay in line!</i>

1090
01:36:01,396 --> 01:36:03,694
[ German ]

1091
01:36:03,765 --> 01:36:06,131
- [ German ]
-<i>Jah.</i>

1092
01:36:06,200 --> 01:36:09,169
[ German ]

1093
01:36:09,237 --> 01:36:13,196
Hello, little Tommy.
Little baby, hello.

1094
01:36:14,576 --> 01:36:16,874
- <i>Recognize him? British friend?</i>
- No.

1095
01:36:16,945 --> 01:36:19,937
- [ German ]
- Aaah!

1096
01:36:22,383 --> 01:36:25,011
- Get up!
- No!

1097
01:36:25,086 --> 01:36:27,020
<i>[ Soldier ]</i>
<i>Get up at once!</i>

1098
01:36:27,088 --> 01:36:30,023
<i>[ Aicha ]</i>
<i>No, I don't have a boyfriend.</i>

1099
01:36:30,091 --> 01:36:32,651
<i>I don't know anybody!</i>

1100
01:36:32,727 --> 01:36:35,218
Halt!

1101
01:36:35,296 --> 01:36:39,232
<i>No! No!</i>

1102
01:36:39,300 --> 01:36:41,700
[ Crying ]

1103
01:36:48,343 --> 01:36:50,937
<i>[ Man ]</i>
<i>David Caravaggio.</i>

1104
01:36:51,012 --> 01:36:54,709
- No.
- <i>This was taken in Cairo</i>
<i>at British headquarters.</i>

1105
01:36:54,782 --> 01:36:57,512
July '41 .

1106
01:36:57,585 --> 01:36:59,712
And so was this.

1107
01:36:59,787 --> 01:37:03,188
August '41 .
And this.

1108
01:37:03,257 --> 01:37:05,225
February '42.

1109
01:37:05,293 --> 01:37:08,057
It's possible.

1110
01:37:08,129 --> 01:37:11,428
I was buying or selling something.
I've been to Cairo many times.

1111
01:37:11,499 --> 01:37:15,401
You are a Canadian spy
working for the Allies.

1112
01:37:15,470 --> 01:37:18,564
- Code name: Moose.
-<i>[ Telephone Rings ]</i>

1113
01:37:18,640 --> 01:37:22,940
<i>[ German ]</i>

1114
01:37:23,011 --> 01:37:25,639
<i>[ German ]</i>

1115
01:37:25,713 --> 01:37:27,943
<i>Jah?</i>

1116
01:37:28,016 --> 01:37:30,951
Can you get me a doctor?
I'm sick.

1117
01:37:31,019 --> 01:37:34,455
- [ German ]
- <i>I'm leaking blood!</i>

1118
01:37:34,522 --> 01:37:36,490
- [ German ]
- You want a doctor?

1119
01:37:36,557 --> 01:37:38,650
I've been askin'
for weeks, months--

1120
01:37:38,726 --> 01:37:40,819
We don't have a doctor.

1121
01:37:40,895 --> 01:37:43,261
- [ German ]
- But we do have a nurse.

1122
01:37:43,331 --> 01:37:45,595
Sure, great.
A nurse would be great.

1123
01:37:45,667 --> 01:37:47,658
[ German ]

1124
01:37:47,735 --> 01:37:51,967
Look, give me something.
A name, a code.

1125
01:37:52,040 --> 01:37:54,736
So we can all
get out of this room.

1126
01:37:56,277 --> 01:37:58,643
I can't think
in this heat.

1127
01:37:58,713 --> 01:38:02,308
- It's too hot.
- I slept with a girl.

1128
01:38:04,018 --> 01:38:06,646
I've got a wife
in Tripoli.

1129
01:38:06,721 --> 01:38:11,215
<i>A girl comes up and points</i>
<i>at you,you only see trouble.</i>

1130
01:38:11,292 --> 01:38:14,489
-<i>[ Man ] Fire!</i>
-<i>[ Gunshots ]</i>

1131
01:38:15,997 --> 01:38:18,261
<i>I'll tell you what</i>
<i>I'm going to do.</i>

1132
01:38:18,332 --> 01:38:20,994
This is your nurse,
by the way.

1133
01:38:21,069 --> 01:38:23,867
She's Muslim, so she'll understand
all of this.

1134
01:38:23,938 --> 01:38:27,897
What's the punishment for adultery?
Let's leave it at that.

1135
01:38:27,975 --> 01:38:31,433
You're married and you were
fucking another woman, so that's, uh--

1136
01:38:32,980 --> 01:38:35,881
- Is it the hands that are cut off?
- [ Gasps ]

1137
01:38:35,950 --> 01:38:38,885
Or is that for stealing?
Does anyone know?

1138
01:38:38,953 --> 01:38:42,150
Well, you must know.
You were brought up in Libya, yes?

1139
01:38:42,223 --> 01:38:44,691
- Don't cut me.
- Or was it Toronto?

1140
01:38:44,759 --> 01:38:47,694
-<i>[ Telephone Rings ]</i>
- Ten fingers.

1141
01:38:47,762 --> 01:38:49,696
How about this?

1142
01:38:49,764 --> 01:38:52,494
You give me a name for every finger.
It doesn't matter who.

1143
01:38:52,567 --> 01:38:55,536
<i>I get something,</i>
<i>you keep something.</i>

1144
01:38:55,603 --> 01:38:57,901
- <i>I'm trying to be reasonable.</i>
- Don't cut me. Come on!

1145
01:39:02,243 --> 01:39:04,302
Are thumbs fingers?

1146
01:39:05,947 --> 01:39:08,245
[ German ]

1147
01:39:12,420 --> 01:39:15,150
- I get no help from these people.
- Telephone.

1148
01:39:15,223 --> 01:39:19,319
<i>I'm sick of this room, I'm sick of</i>
<i>this heat and I'm sick of this phone!</i>

1149
01:39:19,393 --> 01:39:22,556
- [ German ]
- [ German ]

1150
01:39:22,630 --> 01:39:26,760
- [ German ]
- [ German ]

1151
01:39:26,834 --> 01:39:28,699
- [ German ]
-<i>Ah! The Geneva Convention!</i>

1152
01:39:28,770 --> 01:39:32,103
Hey, come on!
You can't do that!

1153
01:39:32,173 --> 01:39:34,664
- Come over here.
- I'll give you names.

1154
01:39:34,742 --> 01:39:37,905
- <i>You!</i>
- <i>I'll give you names!</i>

1155
01:39:37,979 --> 01:39:40,004
- Come on!
- What names did you say?

1156
01:39:40,081 --> 01:39:44,575
<i>Aaah! Aaah! Let me think!</i>
<i>Just let me think!</i>

1157
01:39:44,652 --> 01:39:47,883
<i>I can't think! I know them!</i>
<i>Please, let me think!</i>

1158
01:39:47,955 --> 01:39:50,219
I promise!
Oh, please, please, no!

1159
01:39:50,291 --> 01:39:53,419
- What name did you say? I knew them!
- Come on!

1160
01:39:53,494 --> 01:39:56,759
- I can't think of any names!
Not my hands! Oh, dear God!
- <i>What are you waiting for?</i>

1161
01:39:56,831 --> 01:39:59,891
Jesus Christ!
Jesus Christ, no!

1162
01:39:59,967 --> 01:40:02,527
I promise!
Oh, please, not my hands!

1163
01:40:02,603 --> 01:40:06,699
<i>No!Jesus!</i>
<i>Jesus! Oh, dear God!</i>

1164
01:40:06,774 --> 01:40:08,639
- <i>Please don't cut me!</i>
- Come on!

1165
01:40:08,709 --> 01:40:11,303
Aaah!
No!

1166
01:40:11,379 --> 01:40:13,540
<i>Please don't cut!</i>

1167
01:40:13,614 --> 01:40:18,517
<i>[ Screaming ]</i>
<i>Don't!</i>

1168
01:40:18,586 --> 01:40:22,181
<i>[ Caravaggio ]</i>
<i>The man who took my thumbs?</i>

1169
01:40:22,256 --> 01:40:26,249
<i>I found him eventually.</i>
<i>I killed him.</i>

1170
01:40:26,327 --> 01:40:28,921
The man who took my photograph?
I found him too.

1171
01:40:28,996 --> 01:40:33,194
That took me a year.
He's dead.

1172
01:40:33,267 --> 01:40:35,531
Another man
showed the Germans...

1173
01:40:35,603 --> 01:40:38,401
a way to get
their spies into Cairo.

1174
01:40:38,472 --> 01:40:41,737
I've been
looking for him.

1175
01:40:41,809 --> 01:40:44,573
<i>[ Madox ] You can't get through there.</i>
<i>It's impossible.</i>

1176
01:40:44,645 --> 01:40:47,045
<i>[ Almasy ] I was looking again</i>
<i>at Bell's old maps.</i>

1177
01:40:47,114 --> 01:40:49,241
<i>If we can find a way</i>
<i>through the Wadi,</i>

1178
01:40:49,317 --> 01:40:52,115
<i>we can drive</i>
<i>straight into Cairo.</i>

1179
01:40:52,186 --> 01:40:54,984
- This whole spur is a real possibility.
-<i>So on Thursday,</i>

1180
01:40:55,056 --> 01:40:57,752
you don't trust Bell's map, Bell was
a fool, Bell couldn't draw a map.

1181
01:40:57,825 --> 01:41:00,658
But on Friday,
he's suddenly infallible.

1182
01:41:00,728 --> 01:41:03,629
- And where are the expedition maps?
- In my room.

1183
01:41:03,698 --> 01:41:06,132
Those maps belong to
His Majesty's Government.

1184
01:41:06,200 --> 01:41:09,033
They shouldn't be left lying around for
any Tom, Dick or Harry to have sight of.

1185
01:41:09,103 --> 01:41:11,697
What on earth's
the matter with you?

1186
01:41:11,772 --> 01:41:15,003
Don't be so bloody naive!
You know there's a war breaking out!

1187
01:41:22,116 --> 01:41:24,311
This arrived this morning.

1188
01:41:24,385 --> 01:41:26,649
''By order of
the British Government,

1189
01:41:26,721 --> 01:41:31,090
all international expeditions
to be aborted by May, 1 939.''

1190
01:41:34,528 --> 01:41:38,020
What do they care
about our maps?

1191
01:41:38,099 --> 01:41:40,567
What do we find
in the desert?

1192
01:41:40,635 --> 01:41:43,229
Arrowheads,
spears.

1193
01:41:43,304 --> 01:41:46,239
In a war, if you own the desert,
you own North Africa.

1194
01:41:46,307 --> 01:41:48,969
Own the desert?
Ha!

1195
01:41:50,044 --> 01:41:53,741
Um, Madox?
That place--

1196
01:41:56,183 --> 01:41:59,346
That place at the base
of a woman's throat.

1197
01:42:00,955 --> 01:42:04,482
<i>You know,</i>
<i>the hollow here.</i>

1198
01:42:04,558 --> 01:42:06,856
Does it have
an official name?

1199
01:42:08,930 --> 01:42:12,661
For God's sake, man,
pull yourself together.

1200
01:42:23,177 --> 01:42:26,112
<i>[ Announcer ] Nowhere is there any</i>
<i>wild patriotic excitement,</i>

1201
01:42:26,180 --> 01:42:28,239
<i>but everywhere there is</i>
<i>a deep hatred of war.</i>

1202
01:42:28,316 --> 01:42:30,978
<i>The answer lies</i>
<i>with one man,</i>

1203
01:42:31,052 --> 01:42:34,613
<i>and the solid mass of the crowd</i>
<i>surging round his car...</i>

1204
01:42:34,689 --> 01:42:38,386
<i>are a symbol that the British people are</i>
<i>more firmly of one mind today...</i>

1205
01:42:38,459 --> 01:42:41,690
<i>than at any other time</i>
<i>in our history.</i>

1206
01:42:44,832 --> 01:42:46,766
[ Arabic ]

1207
01:42:46,834 --> 01:42:49,894
<i>[ Announcer ] There's a great to-do</i>
<i>in Sandown Bay,</i>

1208
01:42:49,971 --> 01:42:53,805
<i>with rowing and sailing, and</i>
<i>no end of sport for every water baby.</i>

1209
01:42:56,644 --> 01:42:59,408
Sorry.

1210
01:43:02,316 --> 01:43:05,046
I can't--
I can't do this.

1211
01:43:08,422 --> 01:43:11,858
I can't do this.
I can't do this anymore.

1212
01:43:19,934 --> 01:43:23,233
[ Crying ]

1213
01:43:23,304 --> 01:43:26,205
<i>[ Women Singing ]</i>

1214
01:43:40,488 --> 01:43:42,752
I'd better go now.

1215
01:43:45,192 --> 01:43:47,626
Say goodbye here.

1216
01:43:47,695 --> 01:43:51,392
I'm not agreeing. Don't think
I'm agreeing, because I'm not.

1217
01:43:51,465 --> 01:43:53,490
Any minute now,
he'll find out.

1218
01:43:53,567 --> 01:43:55,558
We'll barge into someone.
It'll kill him.

1219
01:43:55,636 --> 01:43:57,729
Don't go over it again,
please.

1220
01:43:57,805 --> 01:44:00,296
<i>[ Continues ]</i>

1221
01:44:08,616 --> 01:44:11,312
Katharine?

1222
01:44:15,256 --> 01:44:17,486
I--

1223
01:44:17,558 --> 01:44:20,652
I just want you
to know I'm--

1224
01:44:20,728 --> 01:44:23,390
I'm not missing you yet.

1225
01:44:25,733 --> 01:44:29,635
You will.
You will.

1226
01:44:32,873 --> 01:44:34,340
[ Gasps ]

1227
01:44:40,815 --> 01:44:44,512
[ Breathing Heavily ]

1228
01:45:01,502 --> 01:45:04,938
-  [Jazz ]
- I believe I'm rather late.

1229
01:45:06,307 --> 01:45:08,832
Good.
We're all here.

1230
01:45:08,909 --> 01:45:13,039
<i>A toast to the</i>
<i>International Sand Club.</i>

1231
01:45:13,114 --> 01:45:15,514
May it soon resurface.

1232
01:45:15,583 --> 01:45:17,483
[ All ]
The International Sand Club.

1233
01:45:17,551 --> 01:45:22,579
The International Sand Club:
misfits, buggers, fascists and fools.

1234
01:45:22,656 --> 01:45:25,250
God bless us, every one.
Oops!

1235
01:45:25,326 --> 01:45:28,921
Mustn't say ''International.''
Dirty word, filthy word.

1236
01:45:28,996 --> 01:45:32,261
<i>His Majesty, die Fuhrer,</i>
<i>il duce</i>--

1237
01:45:32,333 --> 01:45:33,800
Sorry.
What's your point?

1238
01:45:33,868 --> 01:45:36,894
And the people here don't want us.
You must be joking.

1239
01:45:36,971 --> 01:45:40,930
Egyptians are desperate to get rid of
the colonials. Isn't that right, Fouad?

1240
01:45:41,008 --> 01:45:44,307
<i>Some of their best people</i>
<i>getting down on their hands and knees,</i>

1241
01:45:44,378 --> 01:45:46,869
begging to be spared
the Knighthood.

1242
01:45:46,947 --> 01:45:50,405
Isn't that right? Hmm?
Isn't that right, Sir Ronnie?

1243
01:45:50,484 --> 01:45:54,318
What's my point?
Oh, I've invented a new dance.

1244
01:45:54,388 --> 01:45:56,481
<i>Anybody up for it?</i>
<i>It's called</i>--

1245
01:45:56,557 --> 01:45:59,117
It's called
the Bosphorus Hug.

1246
01:45:59,193 --> 01:46:00,888
Madox?

1247
01:46:00,961 --> 01:46:05,421
<i>Bermann?</i>
<i>You'll dance with me? Hmm?</i>

1248
01:46:05,499 --> 01:46:08,434
D'Ag.
Come on, Daggers.

1249
01:46:08,502 --> 01:46:10,993
<i>Let's eat first.</i>
<i>Sit down.</i>

1250
01:46:13,841 --> 01:46:17,242
<i>We'll bathe at Brighton</i>
<i>The fish you'll frighten</i>

1251
01:46:17,311 --> 01:46:20,075
<i>When you're in</i>
<i>your bathing suit so thin</i>

1252
01:46:20,147 --> 01:46:22,741
We'll make the shellfish grin
Fin to fin

1253
01:46:22,816 --> 01:46:25,808
<i>They're playing it far too slowly,</i>
<i>but these were the words,</i>

1254
01:46:25,886 --> 01:46:29,652
actually, before
they were cleaned up.

1255
01:46:29,723 --> 01:46:32,817
Might be a song for you,
Mrs. Clif--

1256
01:46:32,893 --> 01:46:35,327
<i>[ Madox ] You either shut up</i>
<i>or go home! You're completely blasted!</i>

1257
01:46:35,396 --> 01:46:38,194
- Sit down!
- Absolutely right! Shut up! Shut up!

1258
01:46:38,265 --> 01:46:42,702
<i>[ Almasy ] Sorry. Sorry.</i>
<i>I'm so sorry.</i>

1259
01:46:42,770 --> 01:46:45,466
I can't think
what came over me.

1260
01:46:45,539 --> 01:46:48,531
Lashings of apologies...

1261
01:46:48,609 --> 01:46:50,804
all around.

1262
01:46:50,878 --> 01:46:53,938
[ Continues ]

1263
01:47:15,903 --> 01:47:18,565
[ Giggling ]

1264
01:47:20,708 --> 01:47:23,302
<i>[ Song Ends ]</i>

1265
01:47:23,377 --> 01:47:24,844
Thank you.

1266
01:47:26,647 --> 01:47:30,242
<i>[ Slow Song Begins ]</i>

1267
01:47:34,888 --> 01:47:38,153
- Why were you holding his collar?
- What?

1268
01:47:38,225 --> 01:47:41,661
''What''? That boy.
That little boy.

1269
01:47:41,729 --> 01:47:44,892
You were holding his collar.
You were gripping his collar. What for?

1270
01:47:44,965 --> 01:47:47,433
Hmm?
Is he next?

1271
01:47:47,501 --> 01:47:50,163
Are you going to drag him
into your little room? Where is it?

1272
01:47:50,237 --> 01:47:52,137
Is this it?

1273
01:47:52,206 --> 01:47:54,470
- Don't do this.
- I've watched you.

1274
01:47:54,541 --> 01:47:56,907
I've watched you
at garden parties,

1275
01:47:56,977 --> 01:47:59,241
on verandas,
at the races.

1276
01:47:59,313 --> 01:48:03,272
- How can you... stand there?
- Please.

1277
01:48:03,350 --> 01:48:06,217
How can you
ever smile,

1278
01:48:06,287 --> 01:48:10,314
as if your life
hadn't capsized?

1279
01:48:11,992 --> 01:48:14,460
You know why?

1280
01:48:17,064 --> 01:48:19,055
Dance with me.

1281
01:48:20,134 --> 01:48:22,534
No.

1282
01:48:22,603 --> 01:48:25,572
Dance with me.

1283
01:48:25,639 --> 01:48:28,574
I want to touch you.

1284
01:48:28,642 --> 01:48:32,578
I want the things which are mine,
which belong to me.

1285
01:48:35,949 --> 01:48:39,441
Do you think you're the
only one who feels anything?

1286
01:48:39,520 --> 01:48:42,489
Is that what
you think?

1287
01:48:42,556 --> 01:48:46,048
<i>[ Continues ]</i>

1288
01:49:01,308 --> 01:49:04,334
Why don't you go?

1289
01:49:04,411 --> 01:49:08,074
- Get some sleep.
- Would you like me to?

1290
01:49:14,955 --> 01:49:17,788
Good night.

1291
01:49:17,858 --> 01:49:20,725
<i>[ Door Hinges Creak ]</i>

1292
01:50:22,356 --> 01:50:24,290
<i>Hana.</i>

1293
01:50:29,363 --> 01:50:31,661
Kip.

1294
01:50:52,853 --> 01:50:55,947
<i>[ Children Shouting ]</i>

1295
01:51:05,544 --> 01:51:08,775
Just wait.
Don't look at anything yet.

1296
01:51:31,503 --> 01:51:33,562
Wait.

1297
01:51:49,888 --> 01:51:51,981
Kip!

1298
01:52:28,159 --> 01:52:30,627
[ Giggles ]

1299
01:52:30,695 --> 01:52:33,255
[ Laughs ]

1300
01:52:51,883 --> 01:52:55,842
[ Gasps, Laughs ]

1301
01:53:12,704 --> 01:53:15,036
Oh, thank you!

1302
01:53:16,041 --> 01:53:18,168
Mmm!

1303
01:53:31,823 --> 01:53:35,782
If one night I didn't come
to see you,

1304
01:53:37,295 --> 01:53:39,855
what would you do?

1305
01:53:39,931 --> 01:53:42,764
I try not
to expect you.

1306
01:53:45,637 --> 01:53:49,698
Yes, but if it
got late and...

1307
01:53:49,774 --> 01:53:52,402
I hadn't shown up?

1308
01:53:53,845 --> 01:53:57,212
Then I'd think
there must be a reason.

1309
01:53:58,283 --> 01:54:00,717
You wouldn't come
to find me?

1310
01:54:03,054 --> 01:54:06,615
Hmm. That makes me
never want to come here.

1311
01:54:11,496 --> 01:54:13,760
Then I'd tell myself,

1312
01:54:13,832 --> 01:54:17,097
he spends all day
searching.

1313
01:54:17,168 --> 01:54:20,103
In the night,
he wants to be found.

1314
01:54:25,510 --> 01:54:28,445
I do. I do want you
to find me.

1315
01:54:29,514 --> 01:54:31,948
<i>I do want</i>
<i>to be found.</i>

1316
01:54:49,467 --> 01:54:52,061
I was looking for
Lieutenant Singh.

1317
01:54:52,137 --> 01:54:56,198
- He's sleeping.
- Only we've got to go to work.

1318
01:54:56,274 --> 01:54:58,742
I'll tell him.

1319
01:54:59,944 --> 01:55:02,538
What is it?
Is it a mine?

1320
01:55:02,614 --> 01:55:05,344
It's a bomb
by a viaduct.

1321
01:55:06,651 --> 01:55:09,313
- Does he have to go?
- Beg pardon?

1322
01:55:09,387 --> 01:55:13,323
What if you couldn't find him?
Sergeant, not today. Not this morning.

1323
01:55:13,391 --> 01:55:17,327
- What's happening? Am I needed?
- Afraid so, sir.

1324
01:55:18,396 --> 01:55:21,490
<i>Don't go.</i>
<i>I'm frightened.</i>

1325
01:55:21,566 --> 01:55:24,535
This is what I do.

1326
01:55:24,602 --> 01:55:27,594
I do this
every day.

1327
01:55:46,591 --> 01:55:48,582
Hardy!

1328
01:55:48,660 --> 01:55:51,823
Serial number
K-K-I-P...

1329
01:55:51,896 --> 01:55:54,694
2-6-0-0.

1330
01:55:54,766 --> 01:55:57,758
<i>K-K-I-P2600, sir!</i>

1331
01:55:57,836 --> 01:56:00,327
I'll get the oxygen.

1332
01:56:23,261 --> 01:56:27,857
<i>[ Engines Roaring,</i>
<i>People Cheering ]</i>

1333
01:56:50,054 --> 01:56:53,353
<i>[ Distant Rumbling ]</i>

1334
01:56:56,661 --> 01:56:59,653
<i>Hardy, what's happening?</i>

1335
01:56:59,731 --> 01:57:02,700
<i>[ Hardy ] Can't see, sir!</i>
<i>It's from the road!</i>

1336
01:57:04,235 --> 01:57:07,534
- Corporal?
- [ Panting ]

1337
01:57:07,605 --> 01:57:11,006
Tanks, sir!
I don't know what it's about!

1338
01:57:11,075 --> 01:57:14,010
- Stop 'em!
- Stop!

1339
01:57:14,078 --> 01:57:16,444
-<i>[ Cheering Continues ]</i>
- Stop!

1340
01:57:16,514 --> 01:57:19,915
- Hardy!
- Stop! Stop!

1341
01:57:19,984 --> 01:57:22,077
What is this,
a bloody carnival?

1342
01:57:22,153 --> 01:57:24,178
The fuse has snapped!

1343
01:57:24,255 --> 01:57:28,089
- <i>What's happened? Is it armed?</i>
- [ Gasps ]

1344
01:57:28,159 --> 01:57:31,526
-<i>[ Cheering Continues ]</i>
- Hang on a second.

1345
01:57:31,596 --> 01:57:33,461
<i>I'll be right with you.</i>

1346
01:57:33,531 --> 01:57:36,898
<i>Can you see</i>
<i>the detonator, sir?</i>

1347
01:57:36,968 --> 01:57:39,801
You've got to cut it, sir.
That frost won't last.

1348
01:57:41,172 --> 01:57:44,141
Stop! Stop!
Slow down!

1349
01:57:44,209 --> 01:57:48,270
- <i>[ Cheering Continues ]</i>
- [ Boards Creaking ]

1350
01:57:48,346 --> 01:57:51,747
Stop! Stop!
Slow down!

1351
01:57:51,816 --> 01:57:54,580
- Go away!
- Yes, sir.

1352
01:57:54,652 --> 01:57:58,418
- This is making me incredibly angry.
- I know, sir.

1353
01:57:59,490 --> 01:58:01,549
<i>Watch out!</i>
<i>That'll burn!</i>

1354
01:58:01,626 --> 01:58:03,457
Ow!

1355
01:58:03,528 --> 01:58:08,295
<i>[ Cheering Continues ]</i>

1356
01:58:08,366 --> 01:58:10,766
<i>Can you feel 'em?</i>

1357
01:58:13,204 --> 01:58:16,071
<i>[ Cheering Continues ]</i>

1358
01:58:20,712 --> 01:58:23,180
Cut it, sir.

1359
01:58:23,248 --> 01:58:25,739
- <i>You've gotta cut it!</i>
- I don't even know if
this is the right wire.

1360
01:58:25,817 --> 01:58:29,412
<i>Choose.Just choose a loop</i>
<i>and cut it.</i>

1361
01:58:29,487 --> 01:58:32,183
-<i>[ Tanks Stop ]</i>
-<i>[ Clipping Sound ]</i>

1362
01:58:43,835 --> 01:58:46,861
<i>[ Cheering Continues ]</i>

1363
01:58:51,676 --> 01:58:55,203
Get a blanket! Spaulding, get a blanket
for Lieutenant!

1364
01:58:55,280 --> 01:58:58,807
Sarge! Sarge!
It's over, sir! It's over!

1365
01:58:58,883 --> 01:59:01,875
-Jerry's surrendered!
- Yeah-ha!

1366
01:59:03,588 --> 01:59:06,819
[ Laughing ]

1367
01:59:06,891 --> 01:59:08,825
Sir, congratulations.

1368
01:59:10,662 --> 01:59:15,793
<i>Heaven</i>
<i>I'm in heaven</i>

1369
01:59:15,867 --> 01:59:18,597
Kip? Kip?

1370
01:59:18,670 --> 01:59:20,604
Kip!

1371
01:59:20,672 --> 01:59:24,472
<i>And my heart beats</i>
<i>so that I can hardly speak</i>

1372
01:59:24,542 --> 01:59:29,673
<i>And I seem to find</i>
<i>the happiness I seek</i>

1373
01:59:29,747 --> 01:59:32,045
Hey, we're goin' home!

1374
01:59:32,116 --> 01:59:37,110
<i>When we're out together</i>
<i>dancing cheek to cheek</i>

1375
01:59:37,455 --> 01:59:41,687
-<i>[ Thunder Rumbling ]</i>
- It's raining.

1376
01:59:43,561 --> 01:59:45,927
[ Laughing ]

1377
01:59:45,997 --> 01:59:49,763
<i>And the cares that hung</i>
<i>around me through the week</i>

1378
01:59:49,834 --> 01:59:52,462
[ Laughing ]

1379
01:59:52,537 --> 02:00:00,239
<i>Seem to vanish like</i>
<i>a gambler's lucky streak</i>

1380
02:00:00,311 --> 02:00:04,543
<i>When we're out together</i>
<i>dancing cheek to cheek</i>

1381
02:00:07,352 --> 02:00:10,844
<i>Oh, I love to</i>
<i>climb a mountain</i>

1382
02:00:10,922 --> 02:00:14,358
<i>And to reach</i>
<i>the highest peak</i>

1383
02:00:14,425 --> 02:00:18,191
<i>But it doesn't thrill me</i>
<i>half as much</i>

1384
02:00:18,262 --> 02:00:21,754
-<i>As dancing cheek to cheek</i>
- [ Shouting, Laughing ]

1385
02:00:25,670 --> 02:00:28,138
Kip, come and
dance with us.

1386
02:00:28,206 --> 02:00:30,436
- Later.
- <i>Oh, come on.</i>

1387
02:00:33,277 --> 02:00:37,111
[ Laughing ]
Clap now.

1388
02:00:37,181 --> 02:00:39,376
Yeah.

1389
02:00:42,754 --> 02:00:46,781
[ Singing In Italian ]

1390
02:00:55,566 --> 02:00:58,626
<i>Come on, Sarge!</i>
<i>Let's raise that flag!</i>

1391
02:00:58,703 --> 02:01:01,069
Hardy's coming!

1392
02:01:02,206 --> 02:01:04,640
Here comes the bomb squad!

1393
02:01:04,709 --> 02:01:08,145
[ Shouting ]

1394
02:01:11,215 --> 02:01:13,342
Hey, where's my helmet?

1395
02:01:13,418 --> 02:01:16,478
Go on,
Sergeant Hardy!

1396
02:01:22,360 --> 02:01:25,124
[ Cheering ]

1397
02:01:25,196 --> 02:01:27,994
Bring 'em home!

1398
02:01:28,065 --> 02:01:30,795
[ People Chanting ]
Hardy! Hardy! Hardy!

1399
02:01:33,971 --> 02:01:35,871
[ Explosion ]

1400
02:01:35,940 --> 02:01:39,808
What was that?
[ Giggling ]

1401
02:01:42,780 --> 02:01:45,214
<i>[ Man Sobbing ] I'm never going</i>
<i>to forgive myself.</i>

1402
02:01:45,283 --> 02:01:47,808
<i>I'm never going</i>
<i>to bloody forgive myself.</i>

1403
02:01:51,155 --> 02:01:54,386
Sergeant Hardy, sir.
It was booby-trapped.

1404
02:01:54,459 --> 02:01:58,190
They was runnin' up the Union Jack, sir,
up on that statue.

1405
02:01:58,262 --> 02:02:01,493
- It just went off, sir.
-<i>[ Woman Crying ]</i>

1406
02:02:01,566 --> 02:02:04,967
Sergeant Hardy climbed up,
Sir,just for a lark, sir.

1407
02:02:05,036 --> 02:02:07,095
It should've been me.
It was my idea.

1408
02:02:07,171 --> 02:02:10,402
- Sir, you don't wanna look.
- Ooh.

1409
02:02:10,475 --> 02:02:12,500
Who's that girl?

1410
02:02:12,577 --> 02:02:15,375
His fiancee, sir.

1411
02:02:15,446 --> 02:02:19,644
- Hardy's?
- He kept it a bit dark.

1412
02:02:27,758 --> 02:02:29,692
Kip?

1413
02:02:30,761 --> 02:02:33,059
Kip, it's me.

1414
02:02:34,265 --> 02:02:37,200
<i>I'm so sorry about</i>
<i>what happened.</i>

1415
02:02:38,536 --> 02:02:41,664
<i>Can I talk to you?</i>
<i>Kip?</i>

1416
02:02:43,441 --> 02:02:46,376
Kip, why won't
you talk to me?

1417
02:02:49,580 --> 02:02:51,844
[ Whispers ]
Oh, Kip.

1418
02:02:55,853 --> 02:02:58,287
Oh, let me come in!

1419
02:03:24,615 --> 02:03:27,948
<i>[ Almasy ]</i>
<i>Hana tells me you're leaving.</i>

1420
02:03:28,019 --> 02:03:30,453
<i>[ Caravaggio ]</i>
<i>There's going to be trials.</i>

1421
02:03:30,521 --> 02:03:32,785
<i>They want me to interpret.</i>

1422
02:03:32,857 --> 02:03:35,724
<i>Don't they know</i>
<i>I'm allergic to courtrooms?</i>

1423
02:03:40,231 --> 02:03:42,165
So...

1424
02:03:43,968 --> 02:03:46,232
I come across
the hospital convoy.

1425
02:03:46,304 --> 02:03:49,296
<i>They're looking</i>
<i>for this stuff.</i>

1426
02:03:49,373 --> 02:03:51,739
<i>This nurse, Mary,</i>

1427
02:03:51,809 --> 02:03:54,243
<i>tells me about</i>
<i>you and Hana...</i>

1428
02:03:54,312 --> 02:03:56,746
<i>hiding in some</i>
<i>monastery in</i>--

1429
02:03:56,814 --> 02:04:00,045
What do you call it?
Retreat?

1430
02:04:00,117 --> 02:04:02,517
How you came
out of the desert...

1431
02:04:02,587 --> 02:04:06,853
and you were burned
and you didn't remember your name,

1432
02:04:06,924 --> 02:04:09,518
but you knew the words
to every song that ever was...

1433
02:04:09,594 --> 02:04:13,496
and you had one possession:
a copy of Herodotus.

1434
02:04:13,564 --> 02:04:16,124
And it was filled...

1435
02:04:16,200 --> 02:04:18,464
with letters and cuttings.

1436
02:04:19,670 --> 02:04:22,104
Then I knew it was you.

1437
02:04:24,742 --> 02:04:27,336
Me?

1438
02:04:37,855 --> 02:04:39,789
I saw you...

1439
02:04:39,857 --> 02:04:44,817
<i>writing in that book</i>
<i>at the embassy in Cairo...</i>

1440
02:04:46,430 --> 02:04:50,389
when I had thumbs
and you had a face...

1441
02:04:50,468 --> 02:04:52,459
and a name.

1442
02:04:52,536 --> 02:04:54,470
<i>I see.</i>

1443
02:04:55,873 --> 02:04:58,171
Before you went
over to the Germans,

1444
02:04:58,242 --> 02:05:02,975
<i>before you found a way to get</i>
<i>Rommel's spy across the desert</i>
<i>and inside British headquarters.</i>

1445
02:05:03,047 --> 02:05:05,345
He took some
pretty good photographs.

1446
02:05:05,416 --> 02:05:08,817
I saw mine in that
torture room in Tobruk.

1447
02:05:08,886 --> 02:05:13,220
So, it made an impression.

1448
02:05:13,290 --> 02:05:17,727
I had to get back to the desert.
I'd made a promise.

1449
02:05:17,795 --> 02:05:19,888
The rest meant
nothing to me.

1450
02:05:19,964 --> 02:05:22,455
What did you say?

1451
02:05:22,533 --> 02:05:26,025
That the rest...
meant nothing to me.

1452
02:05:26,103 --> 02:05:28,663
There was a result
to what you did.

1453
02:05:28,739 --> 02:05:32,266
It wasn't just another expedition.
It did this.

1454
02:05:32,343 --> 02:05:35,312
<i>If the British hadn't</i>
<i>unearthed that photographer,</i>

1455
02:05:35,379 --> 02:05:37,472
<i>thousands of people</i>
<i>could have died.</i>

1456
02:05:37,548 --> 02:05:41,109
Thousands of people <i>did</i> die.
Just different people.

1457
02:05:41,185 --> 02:05:45,349
- Yes, like Madox.
- What?

1458
02:05:45,423 --> 02:05:48,221
You know he shot himself,
your partner,

1459
02:05:48,292 --> 02:05:50,886
- <i>when he found out you were a spy.</i>
- What?

1460
02:05:50,961 --> 02:05:53,088
<i>[ Breathing Heavily ]</i>

1461
02:05:53,164 --> 02:05:57,760
Madox thought
I was a spy? No.

1462
02:05:57,835 --> 02:06:01,032
<i>No, I was never a spy.</i>

1463
02:06:01,105 --> 02:06:03,665
It's ghastly.
It's like a witch hunt.

1464
02:06:03,741 --> 02:06:06,175
Anybody remotely foreign
is suddenly a spy.

1465
02:06:06,243 --> 02:06:08,734
- So watch out.
- Right.

1466
02:06:08,813 --> 02:06:12,146
We didn't care about
countries, did we?

1467
02:06:12,216 --> 02:06:15,049
Brits, Arabs,
Hungarians, Germans--

1468
02:06:15,119 --> 02:06:17,383
None of that mattered, did it?
It was something finer than that.

1469
02:06:17,455 --> 02:06:20,322
Yes, it was.

1470
02:06:21,792 --> 02:06:24,886
I'll leave the plane
in Kufra oasis.

1471
02:06:24,962 --> 02:06:27,430
-<i>So, if you need it</i>--
- Right.

1472
02:06:27,498 --> 02:06:30,194
<i>Hard to know</i>
<i>how long one's talking about.</i>

1473
02:06:30,267 --> 02:06:33,998
We might all be back
in a month or two.

1474
02:06:37,308 --> 02:06:39,276
Hmm.

1475
02:06:42,980 --> 02:06:47,576
I have to teach myself not to
read too much into everything.

1476
02:06:47,651 --> 02:06:51,178
It comes of too long having to read
so much into hardly anything at all.

1477
02:06:56,727 --> 02:06:59,958
Good-bye, my friend.

1478
02:07:00,030 --> 02:07:01,964
[ Arabic ]

1479
02:07:02,032 --> 02:07:04,296
[ Chuckles ]

1480
02:07:05,436 --> 02:07:07,495
There is no God.

1481
02:07:07,571 --> 02:07:10,870
But I hope someone
looks after you.

1482
02:07:12,710 --> 02:07:16,168
In case you're
still wondering,

1483
02:07:16,247 --> 02:07:19,273
this is called
a suprasternal notch.

1484
02:07:23,187 --> 02:07:26,679
Come and visit us in Dorset
when all this nonsense is over.

1485
02:07:32,630 --> 02:07:34,825
You'll never come
to Dorset.

1486
02:07:44,441 --> 02:07:48,207
<i>[ Caravaggio ] So,you didn't know</i>
<i>Madox shot himself.</i>

1487
02:07:51,382 --> 02:07:53,316
No.

1488
02:07:53,384 --> 02:07:56,080
And you didn't kill
the Cliftons?

1489
02:07:56,153 --> 02:07:59,714
[ Breathing Heavily ]

1490
02:08:04,028 --> 02:08:05,996
Sh--

1491
02:08:08,165 --> 02:08:10,929
<i>[ Breathing Heavily ]</i>

1492
02:08:12,269 --> 02:08:14,203
She--

1493
02:08:14,271 --> 02:08:17,263
<i>[ Breathing Heavily ]</i>

1494
02:08:17,341 --> 02:08:20,208
She die--

1495
02:08:20,277 --> 02:08:22,268
She--
I can't.

1496
02:08:26,283 --> 02:08:28,217
Well,

1497
02:08:29,420 --> 02:08:32,014
maybe I did.

1498
02:08:36,126 --> 02:08:38,890
Maybe I did.

1499
02:08:38,963 --> 02:08:42,194
[ Engine Roaring ]

1500
02:08:45,336 --> 02:08:48,134
<i>[ Almasy ] I was packing up</i>
<i>our base camp...</i>

1501
02:08:48,205 --> 02:08:50,935
<i>at the Cave of Swimmers.</i>

1502
02:08:51,008 --> 02:08:55,672
<i>Clifton had offered to fly down</i>
<i>from Cairo to collect me.</i>

1503
02:08:55,746 --> 02:08:58,772
<i>He flew like</i>
<i>a madman always,</i>

1504
02:08:58,849 --> 02:09:01,409
<i>so I</i>--
<i>I took no notice.</i>

1505
02:09:10,027 --> 02:09:11,085
Aaah!

1506
02:09:26,744 --> 02:09:29,941
[ Panting ]

1507
02:09:35,953 --> 02:09:39,980
-<i>[ Whimpering ]</i>
- Katharine?

1508
02:09:40,057 --> 02:09:43,891
Dear God, Katharine,
what are you doing here?

1509
02:09:43,961 --> 02:09:47,397
I can't get out.
I can't move.

1510
02:09:50,935 --> 02:09:53,403
''Surprise,''
he said.

1511
02:09:54,805 --> 02:09:57,467
Poor Geoffrey.

1512
02:09:57,541 --> 02:10:02,274
He knew. He must've
known all the time.

1513
02:10:02,346 --> 02:10:05,782
He was shouting, ''I love you, Katharine.
I love you so much.''

1514
02:10:08,252 --> 02:10:10,686
Is he badly hurt?

1515
02:10:12,323 --> 02:10:14,450
I have to
get you out.

1516
02:10:14,525 --> 02:10:16,959
- Please don't move me.
- I have to get you out.

1517
02:10:17,027 --> 02:10:20,793
- It hurts too much.
- I know, darling, I know. I'm sorry.

1518
02:10:20,864 --> 02:10:22,798
Come on.

1519
02:10:24,068 --> 02:10:26,400
[ Grunting ]
Now!

1520
02:10:26,470 --> 02:10:28,495
[ Whimpering ]

1521
02:10:44,555 --> 02:10:46,887
Why did you hate me?

1522
02:10:46,957 --> 02:10:48,891
What?

1523
02:10:51,395 --> 02:10:54,023
Don't you know
you drove everybody mad?

1524
02:10:54,098 --> 02:10:57,590
Shh.
Don't talk.

1525
02:10:57,668 --> 02:10:59,966
You speak so many
bloody languages...

1526
02:11:00,037 --> 02:11:02,471
and you never
want to talk.

1527
02:11:08,579 --> 02:11:11,878
- <i>You're wearing the thimble.</i>
- Of course.

1528
02:11:11,949 --> 02:11:14,509
You idiot.

1529
02:11:14,585 --> 02:11:18,248
I always wear it.
I've always worn it.

1530
02:11:18,322 --> 02:11:20,756
I've always loved you.

1531
02:11:56,493 --> 02:11:58,484
It's so cold.

1532
02:11:58,562 --> 02:12:01,087
I know.
I'm sorry.

1533
02:12:03,367 --> 02:12:05,801
I'll make a fire.

1534
02:12:10,007 --> 02:12:12,874
<i>Did you get Geoffrey</i>
<i>out of the plane?</i>

1535
02:12:12,943 --> 02:12:15,844
- Yes, I did.
- <i>Good. That's good. Thank you.</i>

1536
02:12:20,684 --> 02:12:22,948
Listen to me,
Katharine.

1537
02:12:23,020 --> 02:12:25,511
You've broken
your ankle...

1538
02:12:25,589 --> 02:12:28,114
and I'm going to have
to try and bind it.

1539
02:12:28,192 --> 02:12:30,752
I think you've also
broken your wrist...

1540
02:12:30,828 --> 02:12:34,423
and maybe some ribs, which is why
it's hurting you to breathe.

1541
02:12:34,498 --> 02:12:37,092
<i>I'm going to have to</i>
<i>walk to El Taj.</i>

1542
02:12:37,167 --> 02:12:41,001
Although, given all the traffic
in the desert these days,

1543
02:12:41,071 --> 02:12:44,700
I'm bound to bump into
one army or another.

1544
02:12:44,775 --> 02:12:48,211
<i>And then I'll come back</i>
<i>and you'll be fine.</i>

1545
02:12:48,278 --> 02:12:50,337
You promise?

1546
02:12:50,414 --> 02:12:53,508
<i>I wouldn't want</i>
<i>to die here.</i>

1547
02:12:54,685 --> 02:12:57,153
I don't want to die
in the desert.

1548
02:13:00,891 --> 02:13:03,826
I've always had a rather
elaborate funeral in mind.

1549
02:13:05,796 --> 02:13:08,162
<i>Particular hymns.</i>

1550
02:13:08,232 --> 02:13:11,167
And I know exactly
where I want to be buried.

1551
02:13:12,636 --> 02:13:16,333
In our garden,
where I grew up...

1552
02:13:16,406 --> 02:13:19,466
with a view of the sea.

1553
02:13:19,543 --> 02:13:22,341
So promise me
you'll come back for me.

1554
02:13:22,412 --> 02:13:25,040
I promise...

1555
02:13:25,115 --> 02:13:27,379
I'll come back for you.

1556
02:13:28,785 --> 02:13:31,652
I promise...

1557
02:13:31,722 --> 02:13:35,021
I'll never leave you.

1558
02:13:38,595 --> 02:13:41,086
You have plenty
of water...

1559
02:13:41,165 --> 02:13:43,326
and, um, food.

1560
02:13:43,400 --> 02:13:46,995
I'll open them
for you.

1561
02:13:51,808 --> 02:13:53,833
A good read.

1562
02:13:57,514 --> 02:13:59,539
Don't waste this.

1563
02:14:03,187 --> 02:14:05,621
Will you bury Geoffrey?

1564
02:14:10,460 --> 02:14:12,587
I know he's dead.

1565
02:14:15,165 --> 02:14:17,429
I'm sorry, Katharine.

1566
02:14:19,436 --> 02:14:21,370
I know.

1567
02:14:28,545 --> 02:14:31,810
Every night...

1568
02:14:31,882 --> 02:14:34,248
I cut out my heart.

1569
02:14:38,755 --> 02:14:41,053
But in the morning
it was full again.

1570
02:14:48,732 --> 02:14:50,666
Darling.

1571
02:14:52,302 --> 02:14:54,293
My darling.

1572
02:15:18,095 --> 02:15:21,292
<i>[ Almasy Muttering ]</i>

1573
02:15:21,365 --> 02:15:24,596
<i>You'd better be ready</i>
<i>about half past 8:00</i>

1574
02:15:24,668 --> 02:15:26,932
Now, honey
Don't you be late

1575
02:15:27,004 --> 02:15:29,905
I'm going to be there
when the band starts playing

1576
02:15:29,973 --> 02:15:32,066
Remember
When we get there, honey

1577
02:15:32,142 --> 02:15:34,770
An invitation
to the strutter's ball

1578
02:15:34,845 --> 02:15:36,972
A very swell affair

1579
02:15:37,047 --> 02:15:39,481
All the highbrows
will be there

1580
02:15:39,549 --> 02:15:43,212
I'll be down to get you
in a taxi, honey

1581
02:15:43,287 --> 02:15:47,451
<i>[ Almasy ] I stopped at noon</i>
<i>and at twilight.</i>

1582
02:15:47,524 --> 02:15:51,984
<i>Three days there on foot,</i>
<i>I told her,</i>

1583
02:15:52,062 --> 02:15:55,998
<i>and three hours</i>
<i>back by car.</i>

1584
02:15:58,068 --> 02:16:00,696
<i>Don't go anywhere.</i>

1585
02:16:01,705 --> 02:16:03,639
<i>I'll be back.</i>

1586
02:16:06,610 --> 02:16:08,874
<i>I'll be back.</i>

1587
02:16:22,959 --> 02:16:25,621
[ Arabic ]

1588
02:16:25,696 --> 02:16:27,994
Just walked in
from the desert, sir.

1589
02:16:29,232 --> 02:16:31,632
<i>Morning.</i>

1590
02:16:44,381 --> 02:16:47,441
Dear golly, where have
you come from then?

1591
02:16:48,518 --> 02:16:50,884
There's been an accident.

1592
02:16:50,954 --> 02:16:53,514
I need a doctor...

1593
02:16:53,590 --> 02:16:56,923
to come with me,
and I need to borrow this car.

1594
02:16:56,993 --> 02:16:58,927
I'll pay,
of course.

1595
02:16:58,995 --> 02:17:02,897
- And I need-- I need morphine.
- May I see your papers, sir?

1596
02:17:02,966 --> 02:17:05,161
What?

1597
02:17:05,235 --> 02:17:08,568
If I could just see
some form of identification.

1598
02:17:08,638 --> 02:17:12,130
I'm sorry, I'm not making sense.
Forgive me, I-- I'm not--

1599
02:17:12,209 --> 02:17:14,700
I've been walking and--

1600
02:17:14,778 --> 02:17:19,647
A woman is badly injured
at the Gilf Kabir, the Cave of Swimmers.

1601
02:17:19,716 --> 02:17:22,412
<i>I'm a member of the</i>
<i>Royal Geographical Society.</i>

1602
02:17:22,486 --> 02:17:25,148
Right.
[ Clears Throat ]

1603
02:17:25,222 --> 02:17:28,658
Now, if I could...
just take your name.

1604
02:17:31,661 --> 02:17:36,325
Count Laszlo de Almasy.

1605
02:17:38,568 --> 02:17:42,629
''Almasy.'' Would you mind
spelling that for me?

1606
02:17:42,706 --> 02:17:45,903
- Look, listen to me, will you?
- What nationality would that be?

1607
02:17:45,976 --> 02:17:50,174
A woman is dying.
My wife is dying.

1608
02:17:50,247 --> 02:17:54,445
I have been... walking--

1609
02:17:55,819 --> 02:17:58,413
<i>I have been walking</i>
<i>for three days.</i>

1610
02:17:58,488 --> 02:18:00,956
I do not want
to spell my name.

1611
02:18:01,024 --> 02:18:04,255
- I want you to give me this car.
- I understand you're agitated.

1612
02:18:04,327 --> 02:18:07,490
Perhaps if you'd like to sit down,
I can radio back to H.Q.

1613
02:18:07,564 --> 02:18:12,524
No. No, don't--
Don't radio anybody!

1614
02:18:12,602 --> 02:18:15,833
Just give me
the fucking car!

1615
02:19:05,288 --> 02:19:07,916
[ Gasping ]

1616
02:19:15,799 --> 02:19:19,997
Stop the car, please.
A woman is dying!

1617
02:19:20,070 --> 02:19:22,595
Listen, Fritz, if I have to listen
to another word from you,

1618
02:19:22,672 --> 02:19:24,697
I'm going to give you
a fucking good hiding!

1619
02:19:24,774 --> 02:19:27,368
Fritz? What are you
talking about, Fritz?

1620
02:19:27,444 --> 02:19:28,877
Well, that's your name,
isn't it?

1621
02:19:28,945 --> 02:19:30,936
Count Fuckin' Asshole
Von Bismarck!

1622
02:19:31,014 --> 02:19:33,744
- What's that supposed to be, Irish?
- Please!

1623
02:19:33,817 --> 02:19:37,753
You have to listen!
Katharine!

1624
02:19:37,821 --> 02:19:40,551
<i>Katharine!</i>

1625
02:19:40,624 --> 02:19:44,116
[ Chugging ]

1626
02:19:52,302 --> 02:19:54,600
Excuse me.

1627
02:19:54,671 --> 02:19:58,607
- I also need to use the lavatory.
- You'll have to wait.

1628
02:19:58,675 --> 02:20:02,475
- It's urgent.
- Sarge!

1629
02:20:02,546 --> 02:20:05,709
Sarge,Jerry wants
to use the lav.

1630
02:20:05,782 --> 02:20:08,114
Says it's urgent.

1631
02:20:10,186 --> 02:20:13,622
- Where are we going, please?
- Oh, up north to the coast.

1632
02:20:13,690 --> 02:20:16,158
Benghazi.
Soon be there.

1633
02:20:16,226 --> 02:20:18,251
<i>You can get your boat</i>
<i>back home then.</i>

1634
02:20:18,328 --> 02:20:22,788
All right, go on then.
Here, you take him.

1635
02:20:22,866 --> 02:20:26,267
I've been up and down
this bloody train all day.

1636
02:20:41,484 --> 02:20:43,577
It doesn't open.

1637
02:20:57,167 --> 02:21:00,534
Aaah!

1638
02:21:24,861 --> 02:21:27,295
[ Coughing ]

1639
02:21:53,523 --> 02:21:55,650
<i>So yes,</i>

1640
02:21:57,160 --> 02:22:00,254
she died because of me.

1641
02:22:03,066 --> 02:22:05,330
Because I loved her.

1642
02:22:08,938 --> 02:22:11,202
Because I--

1643
02:22:14,310 --> 02:22:16,904
Because I had
the wrong name.

1644
02:22:26,856 --> 02:22:31,190
- And you never got back to the cave?
- <i>I did get back.</i>

1645
02:22:31,261 --> 02:22:34,128
I kept my promise.

1646
02:22:35,331 --> 02:22:38,630
<i>[ Almasy ] I was assisted</i>
<i>by the Germans.</i>

1647
02:22:38,702 --> 02:22:41,068
<i>There was a</i>--
<i>a trade.</i>

1648
02:22:41,137 --> 02:22:44,538
<i>I had our expedition maps.</i>

1649
02:22:44,607 --> 02:22:47,701
<i>And after the British</i>
<i>made me their enemy,</i>

1650
02:22:47,777 --> 02:22:51,679
<i>I gave their enemy</i>
<i>our maps.</i>

1651
02:22:51,748 --> 02:22:54,012
[ German ]

1652
02:23:04,094 --> 02:23:06,722
<i>So I got back</i>
<i>to the desert...</i>

1653
02:23:06,796 --> 02:23:09,264
<i>and to Katharine...</i>

1654
02:23:09,332 --> 02:23:11,630
<i>in Madox's English plane...</i>

1655
02:23:11,701 --> 02:23:14,101
<i>with German gasoline.</i>

1656
02:23:18,608 --> 02:23:21,270
When I arrived
in Italy,

1657
02:23:21,344 --> 02:23:24,040
on my medical chart
they wrote,

1658
02:23:24,114 --> 02:23:26,912
''English Patient.''

1659
02:23:26,983 --> 02:23:29,679
Isn't that funny?

1660
02:23:29,753 --> 02:23:33,154
After all that,
I became English.

1661
02:23:36,626 --> 02:23:40,653
You get to the morning and the
poison leaks away, doesn't it?

1662
02:23:44,234 --> 02:23:46,498
Black nights.

1663
02:23:50,573 --> 02:23:53,838
- I thought I would kill you.
- You can't kill me.

1664
02:23:55,211 --> 02:23:57,475
I died years ago.

1665
02:24:01,451 --> 02:24:04,113
No, I can't
kill you now.

1666
02:24:23,273 --> 02:24:26,401
We've been posted.
North of Florence.

1667
02:24:32,382 --> 02:24:36,318
I was thinking yesterday--

1668
02:24:36,386 --> 02:24:38,911
yesterday--

1669
02:24:38,988 --> 02:24:41,456
The patient and Hardy.

1670
02:24:41,524 --> 02:24:43,856
They're everything
that's good about England.

1671
02:24:45,028 --> 02:24:47,496
I couldn't even say
what that was.

1672
02:24:49,399 --> 02:24:53,495
We didn't exchange
two personal words,

1673
02:24:53,570 --> 02:24:56,232
and we've been together
through some terrible things.

1674
02:24:56,306 --> 02:24:58,672
<i>Some terrible things.</i>

1675
02:24:58,741 --> 02:25:02,871
He was engaged
to a girl in the village.

1676
02:25:02,946 --> 02:25:05,540
I mean--

1677
02:25:05,615 --> 02:25:09,779
And us,
he never once--

1678
02:25:09,853 --> 02:25:15,257
He didn't ask me if I could spin
the ball at cricket or Kamasutra or--

1679
02:25:28,605 --> 02:25:31,233
I don't even know
what I'm talking about.

1680
02:25:31,307 --> 02:25:34,242
You loved him.

1681
02:26:57,994 --> 02:26:59,962
Katharine.

1682
02:27:13,476 --> 02:27:16,104
I'm still here.

1683
02:27:17,547 --> 02:27:20,175
You'd better be.

1684
02:27:20,249 --> 02:27:23,047
Don't depend on it,
will you?

1685
02:27:24,354 --> 02:27:27,721
That little bit of air
in my lungs,

1686
02:27:27,790 --> 02:27:31,487
each day
it gets less and less.

1687
02:27:32,962 --> 02:27:35,294
Which is all right.

1688
02:27:35,365 --> 02:27:37,799
It's quite all right.

1689
02:27:39,902 --> 02:27:43,269
I've been speaking
to Caravaggio,

1690
02:27:43,339 --> 02:27:46,274
my research assistant.

1691
02:27:46,342 --> 02:27:49,869
He tells me there's a ghost
in the cloisters.

1692
02:27:51,247 --> 02:27:53,772
I can join him.

1693
02:27:53,850 --> 02:27:55,841
<i>[ Horn Honking ]</i>

1694
02:27:55,918 --> 02:27:58,648
-<i>[ Kip ] Hana!</i>
- It's the boy.

1695
02:28:22,879 --> 02:28:25,313
I'll always
go back to that church.

1696
02:28:26,315 --> 02:28:28,943
Look at my paintings.

1697
02:28:32,989 --> 02:28:35,389
I'll always
go back to that church.

1698
02:28:37,427 --> 02:28:40,760
So one day we'll meet.

1699
02:28:44,333 --> 02:28:47,200
[ Engine Starts ]

1700
02:29:20,236 --> 02:29:22,329
<i>[ Groaning ]</i>

1701
02:30:30,439 --> 02:30:32,373
Thank you.

1702
02:30:36,913 --> 02:30:40,906
[ Crying ]

1703
02:30:44,253 --> 02:30:46,517
Read to me,
will you?

1704
02:30:46,589 --> 02:30:49,319
[ Crying ]

1705
02:30:52,395 --> 02:30:54,829
<i>Read me to sleep.</i>

1706
02:31:17,853 --> 02:31:20,515
<i>[ Hana ]</i>
<i>''My darling,</i>

1707
02:31:20,590 --> 02:31:23,354
<i>''I'm waiting for you.</i>

1708
02:31:23,426 --> 02:31:26,725
<i>''How long is a day</i>
<i>in the dark?</i>

1709
02:31:26,796 --> 02:31:29,060
''Or a week?

1710
02:31:37,506 --> 02:31:39,906
''The fire is gone now...

1711
02:31:39,976 --> 02:31:42,968
and I'm horr--
horribly cold.''

1712
02:31:44,847 --> 02:31:47,611
<i>[ Katharine ] I really ought</i>
<i>to drag myself outside,</i>

1713
02:31:47,683 --> 02:31:50,345
<i>but then</i>
<i>there'd be the sun.</i>

1714
02:31:50,419 --> 02:31:52,683
<i>I'm afraid</i>
<i>I waste the light...</i>

1715
02:31:52,755 --> 02:31:56,020
<i>on the paintings</i>
<i>and on writing these words.</i>

1716
02:31:59,295 --> 02:32:01,195
<i>We die.</i>

1717
02:32:01,264 --> 02:32:03,425
''We die.

1718
02:32:03,499 --> 02:32:07,299
''We die rich with
lovers and tribes,

1719
02:32:07,370 --> 02:32:10,635
''tastes we have swallowed,

1720
02:32:10,706 --> 02:32:13,573
''bodies we have entered...

1721
02:32:13,643 --> 02:32:15,873
and swum up like rivers.''

1722
02:32:15,945 --> 02:32:19,312
<i>[ Katharine ]</i>
<i>Fears we've hidden in,</i>

1723
02:32:19,382 --> 02:32:21,646
<i>like this wretched cave.</i>

1724
02:32:27,623 --> 02:32:30,217
<i>I want all this</i>
<i>marked on my body.</i>

1725
02:32:32,561 --> 02:32:35,530
<i>We're the real countries.</i>

1726
02:32:35,598 --> 02:32:38,123
<i>Not the boundaries</i>
<i>drawn on maps,</i>

1727
02:32:38,200 --> 02:32:40,794
<i>the names of powerful men.</i>

1728
02:32:51,647 --> 02:32:55,583
<i>I know you'll come and carry me</i>
<i>out into the palace of winds.</i>

1729
02:33:03,490 --> 02:33:06,460
<i>That's all I've wanted,</i>

1730
02:33:06,530 --> 02:33:10,465
<i>to walk in such</i>
<i>a place with you,</i>

1731
02:33:10,530 --> 02:33:13,430
<i>with friends.</i>

1732
02:33:13,500 --> 02:33:15,930
<i>An Earth without maps.</i>

1733
02:33:21,310 --> 02:33:24,070
''The lamp's gone out,

1734
02:33:24,145 --> 02:33:27,580
''and I'm writing...

1735
02:33:27,650 --> 02:33:29,915
in the darkness.''

1736
02:34:24,875 --> 02:34:26,800
<i>[ Door Opens ]</i>

1737
02:34:32,680 --> 02:34:35,340
<i>[ Caravaggio ]</i>
<i>Hana?</i>

1738
02:34:35,420 --> 02:34:37,850
<i>Hana, come on!</i>

1739
02:34:39,590 --> 02:34:41,920
<i>Hana,</i>

1740
02:34:43,525 --> 02:34:45,460
this is Gioia.

1741
02:34:45,530 --> 02:34:48,500
- <i>Buon giorno.</i>
- <i>Buon giorno.</i>

1742
02:34:48,565 --> 02:34:50,555
She'll take you
as far as Florence.

1743
02:34:50,630 --> 02:34:52,900
I can get
in back.

1744
02:34:57,540 --> 02:35:00,575
[ Engine Revving ]